WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:56.056 --> 00:00:57.115
[country music]

00:01:01.997 --> 00:01:05.360
Good morning guys.
Today we have a mega road trip ahead of us.

00:01:05.427 --> 00:01:10.031
We're going deep out into
the Arkansas Ozark Mountains.

00:01:10.098 --> 00:01:13.107
I'd say one of the most mysterious

00:01:13.174 --> 00:01:16.231
and misunderstood parts of the country.

00:01:16.298 --> 00:01:17.557
Cruising the Corolla.

00:01:17.624 --> 00:01:19.045
We got until sundown.

00:01:19.112 --> 00:01:23.029
Go get lost in the hollers
and the small towns out in the hills.

00:01:23.406 --> 00:01:27.040
The goal, meet the locals,
and find out what it's really like

00:01:27.107 --> 00:01:29.378
to live out in the Ozarks.

00:01:29.445 --> 00:01:30.328
Let's do this.

00:01:30.822 --> 00:01:32.022
[country music]

00:01:55.616 --> 00:01:58.316
Alright guys,
here we are in Eureka Springs.

00:01:58.383 --> 00:02:01.621
It's gonna be the most touristy part
of the trip today I think.

00:02:01.688 --> 00:02:04.593
It came about because of the water here.

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:07.478
It was known as healing water,

00:02:07.545 --> 00:02:11.795
and people from all over the state
and the region, perhaps the country,

00:02:11.862 --> 00:02:13.930
came down to be healed

00:02:13.997 --> 00:02:17.129
and this town built up
somewhat off a story.

00:02:18.517 --> 00:02:20.564
This place was founded in 1880.

00:02:20.631 --> 00:02:22.396
The healing water craze ended.

00:02:22.909 --> 00:02:25.165
Town went down in population.

00:02:26.002 --> 00:02:28.733
Got really cheap
and then in the 60s and 70s,

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:31.079
the back-to-the-landers came in,

00:02:31.146 --> 00:02:32.697
the artists, the hippies,

00:02:32.764 --> 00:02:34.909
and planted their flag here.

00:02:35.353 --> 00:02:37.407
We're gonna get up on these back streets.

00:02:37.474 --> 00:02:39.865
You can see the Victorian up there.

00:02:39.932 --> 00:02:43.113
This place is known for its architecture,
it's beautiful homes.

00:02:43.180 --> 00:02:44.599
And it's funky. It's quirky.

00:02:44.666 --> 00:02:47.796
It's definitely a unique type of place.

00:02:47.863 --> 00:02:49.408
-How are you guys doing?
-Good.

00:02:49.475 --> 00:02:50.806
You guys from around here?

00:02:50.873 --> 00:02:53.974
From Arkansas, we come to
Eureka frequently, and you're Peter.

00:02:54.626 --> 00:02:56.599
-[laughing] What's your name?
-Eli.

00:02:56.666 --> 00:02:59.128
Good to meet you.
You go on some crazy adventures.

00:02:59.195 --> 00:03:03.226
-Eli, I'm in your home state.
I'm doing a deep dive series on Arkansas.

00:03:03.293 --> 00:03:04.948
What's Eureka Springs like?

00:03:05.015 --> 00:03:06.727
It's amazing. It's eclectic.

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:10.714
It's a four and a half hour drive for us.
We live in South Arkansas.

00:03:10.781 --> 00:03:12.792
-You come all the way up for this town?
-Oh, yeah.

00:03:12.859 --> 00:03:14.673
Come when we can get away.

00:03:14.740 --> 00:03:16.954
Left the kids at home with the dogs.

00:03:17.021 --> 00:03:17.904
Healing waters?

00:03:19.081 --> 00:03:22.105
I don't know if they're healing but…
the town is healing.

00:03:22.172 --> 00:03:24.620
-The new healing waters
are beer at night, right?

00:03:24.695 --> 00:03:25.738
-That's right.

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:28.617
We love the mountains. Love the Ozarks.

00:03:28.684 --> 00:03:31.117
We love the culture up here. The community.

00:03:31.184 --> 00:03:34.043
There's a lot of really cool shops.
Neat places to eat.

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:35.180
It's just relaxing.

00:03:35.247 --> 00:03:39.386
And we go to all the same places
every time but it never gets old.

00:03:39.460 --> 00:03:40.872
What is the Ozarks to you?

00:03:40.939 --> 00:03:44.769
How would you describe them 'cause
I've just entered for the first time.

00:03:44.836 --> 00:03:46.986
-The prettiest place in Arkansas.
-For sure.

00:03:47.053 --> 00:03:49.758
It is absolutely
the most gorgeous place in Arkansas.

00:03:49.825 --> 00:03:51.846
-Okay, I'm going as deep as I can today.

00:03:51.912 --> 00:03:53.358
I'm going into Jasper.

00:03:53.426 --> 00:03:54.849
I'm ending in Mountain View.

00:03:54.916 --> 00:03:57.673
Jasper has gotten a bad reputation

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:00.799
over the years from earlier times.

00:04:00.866 --> 00:04:03.200
Kind of like Harrison if you're familiar.

00:04:03.267 --> 00:04:06.197
-Okay, so old Civil War stuff or what?
-No, racist stuff.

00:04:06.264 --> 00:04:07.147
Oh!

00:04:08.653 --> 00:04:10.534
Like KKK kind of stuff. All that.

00:04:10.963 --> 00:04:13.139
But we went through Jasper last year.

00:04:13.622 --> 00:04:15.243
It's gorgeous. It was amazing.

00:04:15.310 --> 00:04:17.741
Everybody was nice.
It's more like this now.

00:04:17.814 --> 00:04:20.473
-Okay, so that's mostly in the past.

00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:22.061
But it's got that reputation.

00:04:22.128 --> 00:04:23.697
Yeah, from times past.

00:04:23.764 --> 00:04:28.532
This is more touristy than I thought
I'd be out in the sticks.

00:04:28.599 --> 00:04:31.101
-But this is a destination.
-Yes, it is.

00:04:31.168 --> 00:04:32.839
People come from all over.

00:04:32.906 --> 00:04:36.312
This whole area back here is just
historic housing for the most part.

00:04:36.379 --> 00:04:38.808
-Have you been to the Crescent?
-I just got here.

00:04:38.875 --> 00:04:41.643
You've got to do
the ghost tour at the Crescent.

00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:44.872
-Oh man, I don't have time.
-They do it every night.

00:04:44.939 --> 00:04:47.162
-I'll be in Mountain View.
-Oh man, that's horrible.

00:04:47.229 --> 00:04:50.457
You gotta check out the Crescent.
There's a lot of history there.

00:04:50.524 --> 00:04:52.947
I can't believe they all came
for the water, huh?

00:04:53.014 --> 00:04:54.269
-Yeah.
-The healing water.

00:04:54.336 --> 00:04:58.348
The story's behind that because that's what
the Crescent was basically built for.

00:04:58.415 --> 00:04:59.298
-Okay.

00:04:59.365 --> 00:05:02.467
It was a sanitarium
where they were taking care of people.

00:05:02.534 --> 00:05:04.494
-Because of the healing waters.
-Right.

00:05:04.561 --> 00:05:07.739
And there was Civil War troops
coming here to be cared for.

00:05:07.806 --> 00:05:10.956
And then some quack was running it
claiming he could cure stuff.

00:05:11.023 --> 00:05:12.376
A lot of history there.

00:05:17.574 --> 00:05:19.280
-You've lived here 25 years?
-Yeah.

00:05:19.347 --> 00:05:22.187
-What's it like now?
-It's pretty much the same.

00:05:22.254 --> 00:05:24.190
It's the best pace of life ever.

00:05:24.257 --> 00:05:27.977
I moved up towards the Osage area.

00:05:28.044 --> 00:05:32.735
You have neighbors like maybe
once every five miles, you know.

00:05:32.802 --> 00:05:34.893
So you're out, you're by yourself.

00:05:34.960 --> 00:05:36.811
And I absolutely love the thing.

00:05:36.878 --> 00:05:39.066
I'm coming from big city, you know.

00:05:39.133 --> 00:05:41.122
I did eight years in the military.

00:05:41.189 --> 00:05:43.676
So this is my place.

00:05:43.743 --> 00:05:45.371
This is my sanctuary.

00:05:45.438 --> 00:05:47.253
You go anywhere else… listen here.

00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:50.598
So whenever we go to Texas, right,

00:05:51.159 --> 00:05:55.383
you can totally smell
the air quality difference.

00:05:55.450 --> 00:05:57.968
It's just nice here.
It's just another way of life.

00:05:58.035 --> 00:06:00.643
We have people come here
all the time that, you know,

00:06:00.710 --> 00:06:02.696
Arkansas does something to the people.

00:06:02.763 --> 00:06:04.364
And it makes them want to stay.

00:06:04.431 --> 00:06:06.354
-This is my wife.
-Oh, okay, sorry.

00:06:07.233 --> 00:06:09.566
 I thought you were recording, I was like…

00:06:09.633 --> 00:06:12.501
-Did she feel the same way?
-She was born and raised here.

00:06:12.568 --> 00:06:15.105
No way. How was that?

00:06:15.172 --> 00:06:16.915
I was born in the hospital.

00:06:16.982 --> 00:06:18.985
1980, they had a Mayo Clinic.

00:06:19.052 --> 00:06:20.893
Greatest doctors ever here.

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:23.031
But they shut the delivering part down.

00:06:23.098 --> 00:06:25.979
So right after I was born,
no more babies.

00:06:26.046 --> 00:06:27.598
-You were the last one.
-That was it.

00:06:27.665 --> 00:06:30.176
They were wheeling my mom
through the waiting room

00:06:30.243 --> 00:06:32.765
to get to where
they could deliver me safely.

00:06:32.832 --> 00:06:34.950
So what was it like growing up here?

00:06:35.612 --> 00:06:37.699
Safe, magical, whimsical.

00:06:38.327 --> 00:06:40.948
I lived a really sheltered life though.

00:06:41.601 --> 00:06:45.751
Because I didn't see all the dangers
and all the things of the world.

00:06:46.218 --> 00:06:49.502
So when we moved out of here,
it was real eye opening.

00:06:49.569 --> 00:06:51.083
-But now you've moved back.

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:52.698
I always come back home.

00:06:52.765 --> 00:06:55.363
I raise my kids here
and my grand babies are here.

00:06:55.430 --> 00:06:57.050
Okay, still super safe?

00:06:57.374 --> 00:06:58.503
Absolutely.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:01.452
-Everyone knows everyone type place?
-Not anymore.

00:07:02.217 --> 00:07:04.199
But yes, we try our best.

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:08.107
-Has it always been touristy?
That's what we are, a tourist town.

00:07:08.174 --> 00:07:11.530
Always has been, huh?
Ever since the waters in the beginning?

00:07:11.597 --> 00:07:16.251
We White people took those waters
from the Indians and called it Eureka.

00:07:17.366 --> 00:07:22.160
And they moved on and we started building
and the railroad helped us

00:07:22.227 --> 00:07:26.363
build Crescent and start building
our big buildings along the main strip.

00:07:26.785 --> 00:07:28.757
It's burned down a couple times

00:07:28.824 --> 00:07:31.395
and the artists and the hippies
brought it back.

00:07:31.462 --> 00:07:32.558
And we're still here.

00:07:32.625 --> 00:07:34.380
-Super creative place?

00:07:34.447 --> 00:07:35.574
Very. It's magical.

00:07:35.641 --> 00:07:39.753
Have you ever had deja vu or
right time, right place, kind of feeling?

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:40.703
-Yeah.

00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:42.546
It's like that all the time here.

00:07:42.996 --> 00:07:44.076
-Okay.
-Yeah.

00:07:44.143 --> 00:07:46.403
-What's in here?
-Oh, go in.

00:07:46.470 --> 00:07:48.979
-This is all of us.
We made everything in here.

00:07:49.046 --> 00:07:50.747
-You made everything?
-Yeah.

00:07:50.814 --> 00:07:52.755
-Oh, nice. What a beautiful shop.

00:07:53.306 --> 00:07:54.986
Do you two love working together?

00:07:55.053 --> 00:07:57.710
-[both] Absolutely, man.
-[laughter]

00:07:57.777 --> 00:07:58.660
On cue.

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:00.527
We're together 24/7.

00:08:00.594 --> 00:08:03.149
-That's my best friend there.
-Good for you guys.

00:08:03.216 --> 00:08:04.243
Thanks, man.

00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:06.493
I'm gonna cruise up
into this neighborhood.

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:08.612
I heard those are the beautiful homes.

00:08:08.679 --> 00:08:10.535
And then go to a haunted house.

00:08:10.602 --> 00:08:12.303
-Crescent Hotel.
-[both] Yes.

00:08:12.370 --> 00:08:15.123
-Ghost are real. Let me show you a picture.
-For real.

00:08:15.190 --> 00:08:17.347
-You got some ghost stories?
-Oh, yeah.

00:08:17.414 --> 00:08:20.554
So at the Crescent, there's a tabby cat.

00:08:20.950 --> 00:08:22.656
The tabby cat has since passed.

00:08:22.723 --> 00:08:24.513
Now they have a black cat?

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:27.162
-There's two black cats,
but his name was Otis.

00:08:27.229 --> 00:08:31.103
So anyways, the tabby cat is a ghost

00:08:31.170 --> 00:08:32.953
that's still at the Crescent.

00:08:33.365 --> 00:08:34.248
And here he is.

00:08:35.104 --> 00:08:36.083
You see him?

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:38.764
-Might be hard to pick up on the camera.
-It might.

00:08:38.831 --> 00:08:40.145
You truly believe?

00:08:40.212 --> 00:08:43.022
-Absolutely. 100%.
-You have to see to believe.

00:08:43.089 --> 00:08:46.550
You have to feel to believe.
And I know for certain

00:08:47.318 --> 00:08:48.799
that there are spirits there.

00:08:48.866 --> 00:08:51.631
I've never felt anything
negative or malevolent.

00:08:52.065 --> 00:08:55.914
They'll play little tricks on the maids
and move towels and stuff.

00:08:55.981 --> 00:09:00.560
They'll make the sign on the outside
of the door spin that says do not disturb.

00:09:00.907 --> 00:09:02.977
They'll flick lights, pull your covers.

00:09:03.044 --> 00:09:06.500
But nothing, nothing as evil as that ever.

00:09:06.567 --> 00:09:09.111
And I've heard some stories
growing up here.

00:09:09.178 --> 00:09:12.393
I'm gonna do my best
to capture that feeling on camera.

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:14.035
You're gonna have so much fun.

00:09:14.102 --> 00:09:15.916
-I love your fire. Both of you.

00:09:15.983 --> 00:09:17.060
You have a good one.

00:09:17.127 --> 00:09:18.953
-Thank you. Take care.

00:09:24.005 --> 00:09:26.599
This is a cool, funky town.

00:09:27.239 --> 00:09:30.383
It's got some
Nevada City, California vibes.

00:09:31.245 --> 00:09:34.804
It's got almost a little bit of
deep Appalachia

00:09:34.871 --> 00:09:38.948
as far as you feel tucked away
from everything else vibes.

00:09:39.379 --> 00:09:42.803
And this place is just somewhere
you can just walk around.

00:09:42.870 --> 00:09:43.753
It's enjoyable.

00:09:51.050 --> 00:09:52.549
Grand entryway.

00:09:55.210 --> 00:09:58.933
Hi guys. I was told to go to
the most haunted part of this hotel.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:00.211
Where is that?

00:10:00.278 --> 00:10:02.944
So 218 is our most haunted room.

00:10:03.011 --> 00:10:04.187
Okay. Okay.

00:10:04.254 --> 00:10:07.719
It does get booked
so it might be occupied at the moment.

00:10:07.786 --> 00:10:11.308
But the second floor
is kind of just all around.

00:10:11.375 --> 00:10:12.473
It has history.

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:14.313
-It's haunted feel?
-Mm-hmm.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:17.011
[woman] …on an actual tour
with our ghost tour guides

00:10:17.078 --> 00:10:19.808
and it gets access to
the basement downstairs.

00:10:19.875 --> 00:10:21.814
That was the morgue of the hotel.

00:10:21.881 --> 00:10:25.183
They kind of left it all original
back whenever it was a hospital.

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:26.874
-Do you love working here?
-Yeah.

00:10:26.941 --> 00:10:29.462
-It's like stepping into the old world.
-It is. Yeah.

00:10:30.357 --> 00:10:32.004
[Peter] Look at this beauty.

00:10:33.176 --> 00:10:35.411
That's so cool.
That organ right there.

00:10:45.879 --> 00:10:47.796
Near room 218.

00:10:48.753 --> 00:10:49.636
Right here.

00:10:50.210 --> 00:10:53.168
Sir, is this where it's supposed to
feel haunted right here?

00:10:53.241 --> 00:10:54.921
-Yeah. 218 and 419.

00:10:54.988 --> 00:10:57.040
-Have you ever seen the ghost?

00:10:57.107 --> 00:10:58.173
-Do you feel it?

00:10:58.240 --> 00:10:59.786
At the back porch.

00:10:59.853 --> 00:11:02.396
Sometimes they open without wind.

00:11:02.463 --> 00:11:03.563
-Seriously?
-Yeah.

00:11:05.690 --> 00:11:09.866
Well I could guess in the right conditions
this could feel a bit creepy.

00:11:11.092 --> 00:11:13.993
You know, the ghost tours, who knows?

00:11:14.060 --> 00:11:16.413
It'd be interesting to check out though.

00:11:20.026 --> 00:11:23.116
[man] It was originally
one of the best upper echelon hotels.

00:11:23.183 --> 00:11:25.663
Horseback riding,
indoor plumbing, electricity.

00:11:25.730 --> 00:11:27.899
-It was kind of like…
-Ahead of the times.

00:11:27.966 --> 00:11:30.743
-Yeah, best place to go.
-Still is, right?

00:11:30.810 --> 00:11:33.332
Absolutely. It's changed over the years.

00:11:33.399 --> 00:11:36.679
It was a cancer hospital,
it was a women's college at one point.

00:11:36.746 --> 00:11:38.814
The ghost stories? You a believer?

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:40.341
Let's be honest.

00:11:40.408 --> 00:11:44.385
I've been here for 10 years and I've seen
some stuff that was less than logical.

00:11:44.452 --> 00:11:46.386
-I'll leave it at that.
-Like what?

00:11:46.453 --> 00:11:50.483
Just doors opening when they shouldn't,
sounds, eerie feelings,

00:11:50.550 --> 00:11:53.600
people leaving their rooms at 2:00 AM
'cause they get scared.

00:11:53.667 --> 00:11:56.567
-Are you serious? Wow.
-Yeah. Definitely seen that before.

00:11:56.634 --> 00:12:00.134
It was a cancer hospital and the guy
who was running it wasn't a doctor

00:12:00.201 --> 00:12:02.988
and his name was "Dr." Norman Baker.

00:12:03.055 --> 00:12:04.478
I recommend looking him up.

00:12:04.545 --> 00:12:07.295
He encouraged people
to come get better and they didn't.

00:12:07.362 --> 00:12:09.732
He's the doctor that brought people
for the healing waters.

00:12:09.799 --> 00:12:11.433
-Absolutely.
-Okay.

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:13.724
And his magic elixir and everything else.

00:12:13.791 --> 00:12:16.219
So it was a marketing scheme
for the most part.

00:12:16.286 --> 00:12:19.759
More than. He was a charlatan.
He was ahead of his time. He was smart.

00:12:19.833 --> 00:12:23.412
But that message built
this whole place, this whole town?

00:12:23.479 --> 00:12:26.492
The railroad came through here too.
So that helps a lot.

00:12:26.565 --> 00:12:27.480
-Your name?
-Jared.

00:12:27.547 --> 00:12:29.947
Jared, you're awesome.
Thank you, man. Take care.

00:12:30.014 --> 00:12:30.897
[country music]

00:12:52.677 --> 00:12:54.835
Here we are in the town of Kingston.

00:12:54.902 --> 00:12:57.069
Now we're covering big distances.

00:12:57.136 --> 00:13:01.685
That's been one hour in the car
since Eureka Springs.

00:13:06.690 --> 00:13:08.161
This is country out here.

00:13:09.594 --> 00:13:12.480
Nailed the weather today.
Absolutely perfect.

00:13:12.993 --> 00:13:15.286
What do we got here? A little flea market?

00:13:15.353 --> 00:13:17.309
-How you doing, sir?
-Fine, how are you?

00:13:17.376 --> 00:13:19.732
-Good. Are you from Kingston?
-Yeah.

00:13:19.799 --> 00:13:21.590
About six miles from here.

00:13:21.657 --> 00:13:23.703
-Okay. How's it going out here?
-Good.

00:13:23.770 --> 00:13:26.821
Back behind here used to be
an old Blacksmith shop.

00:13:26.888 --> 00:13:27.888
-Okay.
-Years ago.

00:13:28.875 --> 00:13:31.867
This road right here,
we might see one car a day.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:33.883
All day long.

00:13:34.410 --> 00:13:35.469
It was dirt road.

00:13:35.938 --> 00:13:37.232
So it's changed a lot.

00:13:38.122 --> 00:13:40.240
My dad never did drive an automobile.

00:13:41.242 --> 00:13:42.281
-Just a horse?

00:13:43.101 --> 00:13:45.042
We'd come to town with the wagon.

00:13:45.545 --> 00:13:47.062
-Seriously?
-I'm serious.

00:13:47.129 --> 00:13:49.559
-You grew up going to town in the wagon?
-Yeah.

00:13:50.027 --> 00:13:52.641
I'd be behind the mule,
plowing the fields.

00:13:54.281 --> 00:13:55.564
It's changed a lot.

00:13:56.105 --> 00:13:58.716
In fact, this road right here
was the first job I had

00:13:58.783 --> 00:14:02.603
when I got out of high school
is helping pave this road 21.

00:14:03.166 --> 00:14:04.616
-Is this your better half?

00:14:04.683 --> 00:14:06.459
Yeah. We've been married two years.

00:14:06.526 --> 00:14:08.433
-Two years? Congrats.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:10.271
-Newlyweds.
-That's awesome.

00:14:10.338 --> 00:14:12.552
How's that?
Getting right back into the game.

00:14:12.619 --> 00:14:14.585
-That is great.
-How'd you two meet?

00:14:14.652 --> 00:14:15.688
Through church.

00:14:15.755 --> 00:14:18.805
-He jumped the line and asked you
on a date? Or what happened?

00:14:18.872 --> 00:14:21.367
-No. It was the other way around.
-Get out.

00:14:21.434 --> 00:14:23.022
She's started the subject..

00:14:24.797 --> 00:14:27.755
-You love traveling.
You've been to all the lower 48 states.

00:14:27.822 --> 00:14:29.090
The national parks.

00:14:29.157 --> 00:14:30.576
How do you compare Arkansas?

00:14:30.643 --> 00:14:32.506
It's up there towards the top.

00:14:32.573 --> 00:14:35.174
-Where else do you like?
-I love Oregon.

00:14:35.241 --> 00:14:37.606
-But we just got back from Texas.
-Oh, cool.

00:14:37.673 --> 00:14:41.274
I'm from Fort Worth.
I'd rather say I'm an Arky.

00:14:41.881 --> 00:14:44.263
-You're an Arky, okay.
-I don't like Texas.

00:14:44.330 --> 00:14:46.563
Sir, how long does it take
to become an Arky?

00:14:46.630 --> 00:14:48.753
-You gotta be born here?
-I'm from Texas.

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:50.723
-You're from Texas?
-38 years.

00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:52.908
How does one end up here from Texas?

00:14:53.639 --> 00:14:57.683
I come, met my wife
at a revival here at Kingston.

00:14:57.750 --> 00:15:00.649
-We helped a revival. Our church did.
-Okay.

00:15:00.716 --> 00:15:05.705
We had 26 youth that came
and held four nights of revival.

00:15:06.339 --> 00:15:08.046
-How is it living out here?

00:15:08.113 --> 00:15:09.916
-Really great.
-You love it?

00:15:09.983 --> 00:15:12.078
Hope it don't change, but it will.

00:15:12.145 --> 00:15:14.645
You got more of that, right?
More tourists like me?

00:15:14.712 --> 00:15:15.614
Oh yeah.

00:15:15.681 --> 00:15:18.624
You feel the economic spillover

00:15:18.691 --> 00:15:22.212
from Northwestern Arkansas,
the Bentonville area?

00:15:22.279 --> 00:15:24.104
-It's coming.
-You feel that?

00:15:24.171 --> 00:15:26.742
We just sat in on meetings called the IDA.

00:15:27.434 --> 00:15:29.993
They're trying to push
Bentonville and Fayetteville.

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:34.213
Just trying to incorporate
Madison County into their county.

00:15:34.776 --> 00:15:37.799
But all it amounted to
is they're out of land.

00:15:37.866 --> 00:15:39.646
They're wanting to expand this way.

00:15:39.713 --> 00:15:41.184
-How's farming these days?

00:15:41.692 --> 00:15:44.313
It's good right now.
The price of cattle is high.

00:15:44.380 --> 00:15:46.083
But it won't stay there.

00:15:46.150 --> 00:15:48.091
-Okay, so it's good at the moment.

00:15:48.581 --> 00:15:50.603
What was the industry back here?

00:15:50.670 --> 00:15:52.953
Lumber? Farming?

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:53.903
Yes.

00:15:54.430 --> 00:15:55.837
Just outside town here,

00:15:55.904 --> 00:15:59.848
there's some rocks still
and there was a stave mill.

00:15:59.915 --> 00:16:02.727
And staves are what you use
to make barrels.

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:04.553
And my dad and my uncle

00:16:04.930 --> 00:16:08.567
would haul staves to Clarksville
for them to put the barrels together.

00:16:08.634 --> 00:16:10.687
-Your father moved to California?

00:16:10.754 --> 00:16:13.414
He worked a year and a half
and came back and got mama

00:16:13.481 --> 00:16:16.759
and they got married
and my brother was born in California.

00:16:16.826 --> 00:16:18.438
They lived in Compton.

00:16:18.505 --> 00:16:19.918
-Outside LA?
-Yeah.

00:16:20.530 --> 00:16:22.673
But in the 50's it wasn't as bad.

00:16:22.740 --> 00:16:24.081
But they moved eight times.

00:16:24.148 --> 00:16:27.610
He followed housing developments
and cleaned up after them.

00:16:27.677 --> 00:16:31.265
So that's the story, you might have to
get out of town to make your money.

00:16:31.332 --> 00:16:32.283
And then come back.

00:16:32.350 --> 00:16:36.273
I went 1st grade through 12th grade here
and then I taught here 14 years.

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:38.046
-How was that?
-Best life ever.

00:16:38.417 --> 00:16:41.129
None of our kids even when I taught,

00:16:41.658 --> 00:16:42.857
had locks on lockers.

00:16:42.924 --> 00:16:44.243
Nobody stole anything.

00:16:44.310 --> 00:16:46.143
-Still safe out here like that?

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:48.125
Um, to a point.

00:16:48.548 --> 00:16:50.523
-You didn't have meth back in the day?

00:16:50.590 --> 00:16:51.485
Correct.

00:16:51.552 --> 00:16:54.298
-And there's some of that in these hills?
-Yes.

00:16:54.365 --> 00:16:55.248
Is it bad?

00:16:56.300 --> 00:16:57.418
In my opinion, yes.

00:16:58.644 --> 00:16:59.527
You think?

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:01.159
-Meth?
-Yeah.

00:17:01.716 --> 00:17:02.599
-It's bad?

00:17:03.101 --> 00:17:05.463
-It's getting in here.
-It's getting in here?

00:17:05.530 --> 00:17:07.309
It's not going down, it's going up?

00:17:07.376 --> 00:17:10.433
It's going up.
I mean, it's a good place to hide.

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:12.956
Where we live
it's a mile to our closest neighbor.

00:17:13.023 --> 00:17:13.941
-Oh, that's nice.

00:17:14.008 --> 00:17:17.108
A lot of people live in the country
but they come on Saturdays.

00:17:17.175 --> 00:17:19.971
I've got a picture of 150 people
here in the square

00:17:20.452 --> 00:17:21.513
trading and selling.

00:17:21.580 --> 00:17:23.713
-They'd all come out of the hills
for the weekend?

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:26.106
There'd be a fight every weekend.

00:17:26.173 --> 00:17:28.344
-A fight?
-A fist fight or something.

00:17:28.411 --> 00:17:30.261
You guys have calmed down ever since?

00:17:30.328 --> 00:17:31.286
-Oh yeah.
-A little.

00:17:31.353 --> 00:17:33.124
Not all the way though.

00:17:33.191 --> 00:17:35.171
-That's why we're called Booger County.

00:17:35.238 --> 00:17:36.121
-Booger County?

00:17:36.897 --> 00:17:38.317
Loving Booger County.

00:17:38.734 --> 00:17:40.263
What an interesting place.

00:17:41.271 --> 00:17:42.971
We have Grandpa's,

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:45.198
Cobs Corner Market,

00:17:45.265 --> 00:17:47.084
open seven days, groceries,

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:48.981
picnic supplies.

00:17:49.535 --> 00:17:52.030
It looks like it's a restaurant of sorts.

00:17:52.097 --> 00:17:54.332
Maybe a coffee shop. A new coffee shop.

00:17:54.983 --> 00:17:57.443
So there's a little energy
coming into this place.

00:17:59.593 --> 00:18:01.597
-Hey, how you doing?
-Great, how are you?

00:18:01.664 --> 00:18:03.583
-Look at this place.
-Yeah.

00:18:03.650 --> 00:18:05.273
Is it an old pharmacy?

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:07.423
It is an old general store.

00:18:07.490 --> 00:18:09.591
We're getting ready to open up a store.

00:18:09.658 --> 00:18:13.327
We're still working but people are coming
in all the time and buy stuff.

00:18:13.394 --> 00:18:15.409
I'm making a video on the Ozarks.

00:18:15.476 --> 00:18:18.193
-Help yourself.
-So, can I see this map over here?

00:18:18.274 --> 00:18:19.157
Absolutely.

00:18:19.224 --> 00:18:21.653
So is that where we're at, near a river?

00:18:21.720 --> 00:18:24.273
About 15 minutes away
from the Buffalo River.

00:18:24.340 --> 00:18:27.164
Where you are currently,
well, if you can't quite see it.

00:18:27.237 --> 00:18:29.235
-But we're over here.
-Okay.

00:18:30.056 --> 00:18:34.209
And then you just drive
down the road about 15, 20 minutes,

00:18:34.276 --> 00:18:36.341
and then you'll be like…

00:18:36.408 --> 00:18:37.675
-I'm gonna Jasper.

00:18:37.742 --> 00:18:40.493
-Yeah, so Jasper's gonna be over. here.

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:43.023
-That's beautiful, right?
-That's, oh yeah.

00:18:43.090 --> 00:18:44.770
We own a cabin right up the road,

00:18:44.837 --> 00:18:47.578
but we've been coming over here
for about 12 years.

00:18:47.645 --> 00:18:52.039
And we love it so much
and we've seen this building

00:18:52.497 --> 00:18:53.919
empty for the last few years

00:18:53.986 --> 00:18:56.392
and we've always wanted to
open up an outdoor store.

00:18:56.459 --> 00:18:57.758
So, here we are.

00:18:57.825 --> 00:19:00.865
We've been working since February.
We're gonna have a grand opening.

00:19:00.932 --> 00:19:03.147
Can we go back there? I love these boxes.

00:19:03.214 --> 00:19:04.447
It's an old apothecary.

00:19:04.514 --> 00:19:07.866
I mean, you just can't recreate
this stuff these days, you know?

00:19:07.933 --> 00:19:10.698
-No, look around. Help yourself.
-Oh, thank you.

00:19:11.480 --> 00:19:12.539
Oh, this is great.

00:19:13.182 --> 00:19:14.682
See these old boxes.

00:19:16.860 --> 00:19:17.743
See you, guys.

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:19.408
[door bells jingle]

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:20.992
Listen.

00:19:21.059 --> 00:19:22.257
[door bells jingle]

00:19:22.324 --> 00:19:24.363
Old wooden doors. Love that sound.

00:19:24.430 --> 00:19:26.909
We've got the old timers, the old stories,

00:19:27.645 --> 00:19:29.333
some new blood coming in.

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:32.092
When I get deep in the interior,
like Appalachia,

00:19:32.159 --> 00:19:35.760
you come in and every town
is going through its own cycle,

00:19:36.166 --> 00:19:37.460
own transformation.

00:19:37.953 --> 00:19:40.372
Some are really grinding on the bottom.

00:19:40.439 --> 00:19:43.623
Others are in this process of coming back,

00:19:43.690 --> 00:19:45.250
reinventing themselves.

00:19:46.080 --> 00:19:48.083
Will these places be filled up?

00:19:48.150 --> 00:19:50.756
Let's say, I don't know, in 10 years.

00:19:50.823 --> 00:19:52.633
Is this a hopping town?

00:19:52.700 --> 00:19:54.203
Do people move back in?

00:19:54.670 --> 00:19:56.573
These businesses come alive.

00:19:56.640 --> 00:20:00.581
I guess it would just be tourism
that would be the main driver here.

00:20:02.220 --> 00:20:04.693
All right, guys. Doing the audiobook.

00:20:04.760 --> 00:20:06.317
Your fellow Americans.

00:20:06.850 --> 00:20:09.907
If you don't want to buy print,
you can listen to it.

00:20:09.974 --> 00:20:12.032
This process is actually quite difficult.

00:20:12.099 --> 00:20:14.218
I'm surprised. The chapter right now,

00:20:14.285 --> 00:20:15.628
Deep Appalachia.

00:20:16.240 --> 00:20:19.487
And so an example of what my week is like.

00:20:19.554 --> 00:20:22.648
I woke up in a small town in Virginia
called Bluefield.

00:20:22.715 --> 00:20:24.392
Nestled in a remote value.

00:20:24.849 --> 00:20:26.303
See, I messed up.

00:20:26.370 --> 00:20:29.241
Luckily, I'm with the pros
at Simon &amp; Schuster.

00:20:29.627 --> 00:20:31.554
I have Christina, we can't see her.

00:20:31.621 --> 00:20:34.073
She's a little camera shy, but she's great.

00:20:34.140 --> 00:20:37.273
And then we have Brennan
at the nerve center over there.

00:20:37.340 --> 00:20:38.859
He's keeping it all together.

00:20:38.926 --> 00:20:40.892
But overall it's a pretty cool process.

00:20:40.959 --> 00:20:44.938
Guys,
this is gonna be available August 4th.

00:20:45.380 --> 00:20:47.866
Also, another thing I wanted to mention.

00:20:47.933 --> 00:20:50.687
In the book
there are ten separate chapters

00:20:50.754 --> 00:20:52.198
that stand on their own.

00:20:52.265 --> 00:20:56.323
We have some of the classics from
the videos like Amish Country or East LA.

00:20:56.390 --> 00:20:57.949
But you can pick up the book,

00:20:58.016 --> 00:21:00.033
go through a story, put it down,

00:21:00.100 --> 00:21:01.868
start anew at another time.

00:21:01.935 --> 00:21:03.768
It's not a huge commitment.

00:21:03.835 --> 00:21:06.964
The beauty of this book
is if you love the videos,

00:21:07.031 --> 00:21:11.044
behind the scenes there's a ton going on
that you don't see online.

00:21:11.697 --> 00:21:14.230
Some of that's in here.
Also, my origin story.

00:21:14.297 --> 00:21:15.873
How I got into doing this.

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:18.966
I never ask for you guys
to like or subscribe on the channel.

00:21:19.033 --> 00:21:24.001
But if you like the mission here,
consider getting a pre-order down below.

00:21:24.068 --> 00:21:27.122
Reason being, more pre-orders we get here,

00:21:27.507 --> 00:21:30.357
the more likelihood it has
to get into the big booksellers

00:21:30.424 --> 00:21:32.566
and actually get out into the world.

00:21:32.633 --> 00:21:35.659
You're gonna love this.
It's a great story about our country.

00:21:35.726 --> 00:21:39.557
Despite the chaotic times,
the turbulent times,

00:21:39.624 --> 00:21:41.941
this is something to get excited about.

00:21:42.008 --> 00:21:44.653
Celebrate our country for its birthday.

00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:46.383
Thanks for being part of this.

00:21:46.450 --> 00:21:47.984
Now back to the Ozarks.

00:21:59.724 --> 00:22:01.717
Look at that DVD collection.

00:22:02.750 --> 00:22:05.062
-Hey, how you doing?
-Hi. What's up?

00:22:05.129 --> 00:22:07.833
-This is a great town. It's cool.
-Yeah, it is.

00:22:07.900 --> 00:22:11.026
You've got a great bunch of locals
over there in the square.

00:22:11.093 --> 00:22:12.611
Have you not been here before?

00:22:12.678 --> 00:22:14.633
-First time.
-Oh, no kidding.

00:22:14.700 --> 00:22:20.013
-First time Arkansas, actually.
-This is the library we started in… 1983.

00:22:20.406 --> 00:22:25.633
In fact, Reba back here and myself
were two of the first ones to do that.

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:27.348
-Reba was in on it?

00:22:27.415 --> 00:22:28.573
-Reba, yeah.

00:22:28.640 --> 00:22:31.283
-All right.
-And we started in a bookmobile.

00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:34.563
And then moved it up
to the fire department.

00:22:35.108 --> 00:22:37.935
And then moved it down here in 2005.

00:22:38.620 --> 00:22:40.951
And we're the friends of the library too,

00:22:41.018 --> 00:22:43.787
so we bought
that building next door, the Annex.

00:22:44.562 --> 00:22:46.636
It's a 1912 drugstore.

00:22:46.703 --> 00:22:48.746
This one here next door.

00:22:48.813 --> 00:22:52.601
It's got library books in there now to sell
if you want to buy one.

00:22:53.901 --> 00:22:57.694
Yeah, Boyson had a store in there.
A drugstore in there.

00:22:57.761 --> 00:22:59.553
-Okay. Great.
-Hey, Kelly.

00:22:59.620 --> 00:23:00.979
-How are you guys?
-Alright.

00:23:01.046 --> 00:23:02.654
-Hey, Kelly?
-Yes?

00:23:03.141 --> 00:23:04.141
Do you know Reba?

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:07.647
-Hi.
-Reba Bollinger.

00:23:07.714 --> 00:23:09.919
She's one of our original friends.

00:23:09.993 --> 00:23:12.547
Me and Reba and…

00:23:12.614 --> 00:23:14.779
I raised my family
eight miles up the river.

00:23:14.846 --> 00:23:16.832
Oh, great. Fantastic.

00:23:16.899 --> 00:23:19.379
She's been with the library since 1983.

00:23:19.446 --> 00:23:20.943
The bookmobile down there.

00:23:21.010 --> 00:23:22.610
-Since the beginning.
-Yeah.

00:23:22.677 --> 00:23:25.732
My husband moved me down here
before he died

00:23:25.799 --> 00:23:28.243
'cause he didn't want
to leave me on the farm.

00:23:28.310 --> 00:23:30.546
Yeah, well. This is Kelly.

00:23:30.613 --> 00:23:33.733
-Hi.
-She is now with the Buffalo Base Camp.

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:36.105
Yeah, over at the General Store. Yup.

00:23:36.965 --> 00:23:40.159
-It's interesting seeing
the transformation of the town.

00:23:40.226 --> 00:23:42.457
You got Reba from the old guard.

00:23:42.974 --> 00:23:46.008
And you've moved in
and you're bringing back this building.

00:23:46.075 --> 00:23:47.691
Trying to bring it back to life.

00:23:47.758 --> 00:23:50.652
You've seen a lot, Reba, huh?
Through the years here?

00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:53.503
-Seen a lot of stuff, huh?
-Yeah.

00:23:54.219 --> 00:23:56.773
Down here in Madison County.

00:23:56.840 --> 00:24:00.310
No matter where I go,
I've seen stuff all over the United States.

00:24:00.377 --> 00:24:02.768
I've been in every state
in the United States.

00:24:02.835 --> 00:24:06.019
I never put a foot in Delaware.

00:24:06.086 --> 00:24:07.601
You drove through it?

00:24:07.668 --> 00:24:10.364
My mind is bad. I'm just 97.

00:24:10.431 --> 00:24:11.950
-You're 97?!

00:24:12.017 --> 00:24:13.753
But anyway… Good for you, Reba.

00:24:14.120 --> 00:24:17.027
She turned the TV off back in the…

00:24:17.750 --> 00:24:19.600
Tell them when you turned the TV off.

00:24:19.667 --> 00:24:23.682
Well, I think it was '79.
My husband's health got so bad that

00:24:24.375 --> 00:24:26.671
I couldn't hear him if he needed me.

00:24:27.560 --> 00:24:32.193
And then after he passed away,
I couldn't make myself turn the TV on.

00:24:32.260 --> 00:24:35.495
One of the grandkids came later
and tried to turn it on.

00:24:36.453 --> 00:24:38.136
She said no thanks.

00:24:38.203 --> 00:24:41.379
When the lightning had burned it,
I had to maintain it.

00:24:42.550 --> 00:24:44.550
What's your secret to a long life?

00:24:46.250 --> 00:24:48.430
You've been reading an awful lot.

00:24:48.497 --> 00:24:50.793
Work hard. I farmed.

00:24:50.860 --> 00:24:53.263
I went out and helped my husband farm.

00:24:53.330 --> 00:24:54.547
Yeah, hauling hay.

00:24:55.110 --> 00:24:58.563
-Tilling, plowing the fields.
-That's what my grandma did too.

00:24:58.630 --> 00:25:00.926
I grew up in a town very similar to this.

00:25:00.993 --> 00:25:03.107
It's not foreign to me.

00:25:03.174 --> 00:25:06.166
So I feel very comfortable here
because you know.

00:25:06.233 --> 00:25:09.784
-Are the locals cool? They let you in?
Or there's some that are holding…

00:25:09.851 --> 00:25:12.138
Okay, so I was told

00:25:12.658 --> 00:25:15.833
the locals would not like
having a new business here.

00:25:15.900 --> 00:25:17.673
That's the rumor I heard.

00:25:18.350 --> 00:25:21.623
I know, I know.
It has been the complete opposite.

00:25:21.690 --> 00:25:25.243
Everybody has come over
and has welcomed us.

00:25:25.310 --> 00:25:27.186
Brought us fresh eggs.

00:25:27.253 --> 00:25:29.853
Brought us sourdough. Brought us cookies.

00:25:29.920 --> 00:25:33.893
It has been the complete opposite.
Coming over to say, hey, welcome.

00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:37.691
We're so glad that that
building is 136 years old.

00:25:37.758 --> 00:25:41.519
And so everybody's just excited
that there's some life back into it.

00:25:41.586 --> 00:25:43.852
When I first came to this town…

00:25:45.218 --> 00:25:47.087
-…it was busy all around.
-Yeah.

00:25:47.479 --> 00:25:50.083
If this is your first time in town,

00:25:50.150 --> 00:25:51.813
take a look at the bank window.

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:53.320
The old safe there.

00:25:53.387 --> 00:25:56.040
Did you go across the street from the bank?

00:25:56.107 --> 00:25:58.934
The safe was built…

00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:03.542
on that pedestal
so if there were a fire.

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:09.483
it would just give way and that big safe
would roll through the front windows.

00:26:09.550 --> 00:26:12.108
-Didn't someone try to steal it
and they drug it out

00:26:12.175 --> 00:26:15.106
and followed the tracks or something?
That's what I heard.

00:26:15.172 --> 00:26:16.228
There's a lot of…

00:26:17.555 --> 00:26:19.393
That could be folklore too.

00:26:19.460 --> 00:26:22.133
Someone tried to steal it
and they drug it out

00:26:22.200 --> 00:26:26.093
with horses or something
and they followed the scrape marks.

00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:27.910
-Nice meeting you, sir.

00:26:27.977 --> 00:26:30.991
The building next door here
is part of the library too.

00:26:31.058 --> 00:26:35.474
Yeah, that's the annex. It's donation only
but you can get whatever books you want.

00:26:35.541 --> 00:26:38.070
-Okay.
-This used to be a bed and breakfast.

00:26:38.137 --> 00:26:40.533
-[woman] Did you show him the bank?
-We're seeing it right now.

00:26:40.990 --> 00:26:41.873
-Here's your…

00:26:42.257 --> 00:26:43.543
-Oh, nice!

00:26:43.610 --> 00:26:45.813
-Cool, cool, cool. Old bank safe.

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:47.295
-Old school bank safe.

00:26:47.362 --> 00:26:50.358
-Look at that. What is this now?
-It's still a bank.

00:26:50.425 --> 00:26:53.091
-Seriously?
-It's a local bank?

00:26:53.164 --> 00:26:55.383
-Get out.
-It's a full functioning bank.

00:26:55.450 --> 00:26:57.332
Anstaff Bank, never heard to it.

00:26:57.780 --> 00:27:00.739
-She's a family of
this original general store.

00:27:00.806 --> 00:27:03.215
She's part of the Bunch family.

00:27:03.282 --> 00:27:07.446
-I brought you some stuff.
-Oh, fantastic. She brought me some stuff.

00:27:07.513 --> 00:27:09.136
-What'd she bring you?

00:27:09.203 --> 00:27:12.049
-I had asked the community for some…

00:27:13.961 --> 00:27:15.785
-My son has a whole bunch more.

00:27:16.554 --> 00:27:19.851
I had asked the community
for some old pictures and stuff.

00:27:19.918 --> 00:27:22.418
This building is on
the National Historic Registry.

00:27:22.485 --> 00:27:23.460
Oh, that's so cool.

00:27:23.527 --> 00:27:26.135
And I had asked the community,

00:27:26.202 --> 00:27:28.702
"Do you have any old pictures or articles

00:27:28.769 --> 00:27:32.100
that I can hang up in here
to preserve part of this history?"

00:27:32.167 --> 00:27:37.108
And so Mrs. Glenda Bunch…
this was the Bunch general store,

00:27:37.175 --> 00:27:38.729
has brought me some. So…

00:27:39.656 --> 00:27:42.709
-Now he has a bunch more
that he'll bring down.

00:27:42.776 --> 00:27:44.291
You can keep that. I have one.

00:27:44.358 --> 00:27:45.510
Okay, I'll…

00:27:46.583 --> 00:27:48.596
Oh, fantastic.

00:27:48.663 --> 00:27:49.643
Oh, yeah.

00:27:49.710 --> 00:27:52.156
Okay, this is the bank. I don't know.

00:27:52.223 --> 00:27:54.784
It's when Dougal and them bought it.

00:27:54.851 --> 00:27:58.311
-So I don't know if you want that.
-I'll take anything. Yeah.

00:27:58.378 --> 00:28:00.528
So this is the bank that we just looked at.

00:28:00.595 --> 00:28:01.654
You can have this.

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:04.817
That's the original sale bill.

00:28:04.884 --> 00:28:06.763
[Peter] Oh, that is so cool.

00:28:06.830 --> 00:28:08.905
-So back in 1998

00:28:08.972 --> 00:28:11.546
when this closed down they did a big…

00:28:12.040 --> 00:28:14.561
It was called the Sale of the Century.

00:28:14.628 --> 00:28:19.067
So there's the outside of it and you can
see right here is that stove right there.

00:28:19.134 --> 00:28:21.484
-It was called the Sale of the Century?

00:28:21.551 --> 00:28:24.831
Yeah, people from Cracker Barrel
and everybody

00:28:24.898 --> 00:28:27.879
was here trying to buy the antiques.

00:28:28.482 --> 00:28:31.485
Businesses and companies
wanted to buy the stuff out of here,

00:28:31.552 --> 00:28:32.978
like Cracker Barrel.

00:28:33.051 --> 00:28:34.352
Things were going so high.

00:28:34.419 --> 00:28:38.733
A little Calumet jar,
canned Calumet went for $40.

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:39.683
Wow.

00:28:40.250 --> 00:28:44.156
One of the locals heard
the guy from Cracker Barrel say,

00:28:44.612 --> 00:28:47.696
-"These hillbillies have gone crazy."
-[laughter]

00:28:49.628 --> 00:28:51.228
Now this you can take…

00:28:51.295 --> 00:28:53.060
I know you have a good camera.

00:28:53.540 --> 00:28:54.807
If you want it.

00:28:56.257 --> 00:28:58.330
-That's the store.
-[gasps]

00:28:58.397 --> 00:29:00.170
[Peter] Oh, that's cool.

00:29:00.237 --> 00:29:02.574
-These are priceless.
-See, look at that.

00:29:02.641 --> 00:29:06.746
How do you feel about someone coming
and putting another business in it?

00:29:06.813 --> 00:29:08.284
Oh, I'm thrilled because.…

00:29:10.215 --> 00:29:11.861
I'm too old to run the store.

00:29:11.928 --> 00:29:15.150
You know,
and nobody in the family wanted it.

00:29:15.217 --> 00:29:17.046
And could keep it up and everything.

00:29:17.113 --> 00:29:19.365
It broke my heart
just to see it sitting here.

00:29:19.432 --> 00:29:22.068
Right. Broke my heart too
and it's not even my store.

00:29:22.135 --> 00:29:23.329
You know, so…

00:29:23.396 --> 00:29:25.718
No, it's great. There's always change.

00:29:25.785 --> 00:29:27.395
You know what I'm saying?

00:29:28.460 --> 00:29:29.638
Fantastic.

00:29:29.705 --> 00:29:31.829
-So if you want those…
-Yes, yes.

00:29:31.896 --> 00:29:34.026
Look. There's the building right there.

00:29:34.093 --> 00:29:35.321
-You got a recipe book?

00:29:35.388 --> 00:29:37.957
-Yeah, she's giving me a bunch of recipes.
-Alright.

00:29:38.024 --> 00:29:41.186
-Take care you two. Nice meeting you.
-Thanks for stopping by.

00:29:41.253 --> 00:29:43.042
-Congratulations.
-Appreciate ya.

00:29:43.109 --> 00:29:44.815
-Wish you the best.
-Thank you.

00:29:48.190 --> 00:29:53.316
So cool, guys, when we just
spontaneously run into scenes like that.

00:29:53.383 --> 00:29:55.077
Real, authentic scenes.

00:29:55.680 --> 00:29:57.817
Culture in action. Life in action.

00:29:58.680 --> 00:30:02.206
And it goes to show you,
no matter where you're at in the country.

00:30:02.273 --> 00:30:04.917
I mean, there's just millions
of different realities

00:30:04.984 --> 00:30:06.669
playing out at the same time.

00:30:06.736 --> 00:30:09.284
What's happening in
Miami right now or Seattle

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:12.548
is literally like going to
another continent from

00:30:13.421 --> 00:30:15.009
being in a place like this.

00:30:15.850 --> 00:30:18.674
And that's what makes
the country so interesting.

00:30:19.715 --> 00:30:21.823
Alright,
here's the situation we're now in.

00:30:21.890 --> 00:30:23.210
No cell phone coverage.

00:30:24.158 --> 00:30:26.276
-Guys, Jasper is that way?
-That way.

00:30:27.012 --> 00:30:28.803
Get to the T in the road.

00:30:28.870 --> 00:30:32.813
Take a left, and then you'll go up
a winding staircase road.

00:30:32.880 --> 00:30:33.763
-Okay.

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:36.988
It'll have a sign says Jasper
right before you get into Ponca.

00:30:37.055 --> 00:30:39.558
-Yeah, my phone doesn't work anymore.

00:30:40.551 --> 00:30:42.858
Ponca's a neat little town
if you got a minute.

00:30:42.925 --> 00:30:44.043
-Ponca? Okay.
-Yeah.

00:30:44.783 --> 00:30:46.435
Take care guys. Thank you.

00:30:47.210 --> 00:30:50.283
So we're now in
no cell phone coverage territory.

00:30:50.350 --> 00:30:52.353
At least for the time being where you

00:30:52.420 --> 00:30:54.784
ask the locals what road to go down to.

00:30:54.851 --> 00:30:57.030
Because you don't travel with a map.

00:30:57.097 --> 00:30:58.443
Which makes it more fun.

00:30:58.920 --> 00:30:59.803
[country music]

00:31:17.885 --> 00:31:20.123
Everyone said you gotta see Ponca.

00:31:20.190 --> 00:31:21.073
So here we are.

00:31:21.661 --> 00:31:24.066
Kayaking, that seems to be the thing here.

00:31:24.517 --> 00:31:25.640
It is kayaking.

00:31:26.568 --> 00:31:29.869
Probably a go-to destination
for the tourists.

00:31:30.383 --> 00:31:32.730
We must be getting close
to the Buffalo River.

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:35.062
Got a farmer's market here.

00:31:37.445 --> 00:31:41.708
Go to Facebook
Ponca Farmer's Market and post it.

00:31:42.362 --> 00:31:43.622
-Is that what I gotta do?

00:31:43.689 --> 00:31:45.708
Ponca Farmer's Market.

00:31:45.775 --> 00:31:48.096
What's the lymphatic tonic elixir?

00:31:48.830 --> 00:31:52.242
Park and come look.
She'll tell you all about it. [giggles]

00:31:55.704 --> 00:31:57.645
I like your business savvy ma'am.

00:31:58.278 --> 00:32:00.523
Like and subscribe.
That's what you were telling me.

00:32:00.590 --> 00:32:02.065
I'm interested in the elixir.

00:32:02.132 --> 00:32:03.653
-That's her.
-That's me.

00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:05.416
What's it gonna do for me?

00:32:05.483 --> 00:32:07.730
-It reduces inflammation.
-Okay.

00:32:07.797 --> 00:32:09.683
For just about anything.

00:32:09.750 --> 00:32:11.867
Snakebite, bee stings, gout.

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:14.176
It helps your lymphatic system.

00:32:14.243 --> 00:32:17.033
-What do you have in here?
-It's poke berries…

00:32:17.100 --> 00:32:19.913
…with apple cider vinegar and local honey.

00:32:19.980 --> 00:32:21.602
It makes a elixir.

00:32:21.669 --> 00:32:24.728
What are my inflammation levels
just by first glance?

00:32:25.600 --> 00:32:27.306
-Oh, by looking at you?
-Yeah.

00:32:29.161 --> 00:32:30.894
I wouldn't be able to tell that.

00:32:30.961 --> 00:32:32.255
Let me see your hands.

00:32:32.870 --> 00:32:34.286
Pretty big.

00:32:34.353 --> 00:32:36.622
-Pretty large.
-They're just big hands though.

00:32:36.689 --> 00:32:38.123
But you don't feel inflamed?

00:32:38.190 --> 00:32:40.218
No. I was a hand model before.

00:32:41.018 --> 00:32:42.430
You've got big knuckles.

00:32:43.322 --> 00:32:45.193
-Big knuckles?
-You have big knuckles.

00:32:45.260 --> 00:32:47.537
-Then I don't see inflammation.
-It was a joke.

00:32:47.604 --> 00:32:49.259
-I wasn't a hand model.
-Oh, okay.

00:32:49.326 --> 00:32:50.738
I never had that career.

00:32:50.805 --> 00:32:51.688
[laughs]

00:32:54.711 --> 00:32:55.683
But maybe.

00:32:55.750 --> 00:32:57.213
I mean, maybe there's hope?

00:32:57.280 --> 00:32:59.175
I wouldn't put my eggs in one basket.

00:32:59.242 --> 00:33:02.194
It would be for like
an axe company or something.

00:33:02.261 --> 00:33:03.543
Alright, I'm gonna do this.

00:33:03.610 --> 00:33:06.648
-I'm gonna let you sample it.
-We're gonna sample.

00:33:06.715 --> 00:33:10.069
Okay. What I've done here today
is this is a tablespoon.

00:33:10.922 --> 00:33:15.025
of this elixir with a can
of the sparkling soda.

00:33:15.512 --> 00:33:18.277
You'll need to add
some sort of carbonated water

00:33:18.724 --> 00:33:20.351
to the elixir to make a drink.

00:33:20.879 --> 00:33:24.531
This is a drink you've made.
You'll drink it in the morning, afternoon.

00:33:24.598 --> 00:33:26.010
Consume the whole thing.

00:33:26.647 --> 00:33:29.735
Your lymphatic system's
gonna pick up what's there.

00:33:29.802 --> 00:33:32.015
-You're assisting your lymph system.
-Okay.

00:33:32.082 --> 00:33:33.729
And it's gonna gather waste.

00:33:34.819 --> 00:33:38.489
It's gonna distribute it down to
your liver and kidney. You'll process it.

00:33:38.556 --> 00:33:42.002
The next morning,
when you expel, you just feel better.

00:33:42.600 --> 00:33:45.213
-It sounds great.
-It's captured a lot of…

00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:46.574
Who doesn't want that?

00:33:47.520 --> 00:33:49.655
Nobody. Everybody should want this.

00:33:49.722 --> 00:33:51.168
Okay. I'm in. I'm in.

00:33:51.830 --> 00:33:54.932
This is more information
about the elixir.

00:33:55.446 --> 00:33:59.219
Instructions on how to use it and how to
reach me if you have any questions.

00:33:59.286 --> 00:34:01.368
-So if I have problems, I reach you?

00:34:01.435 --> 00:34:03.419
-You can call me.
-Give you a call. Wow.

00:34:03.486 --> 00:34:05.819
I like your customer service.
That's top notch.

00:34:05.886 --> 00:34:06.944
Thank you.

00:34:07.011 --> 00:34:09.683
People don't have problems.
They usually want more.

00:34:09.750 --> 00:34:11.053
-They want more. Okay.

00:34:11.120 --> 00:34:12.290
Ladies, take care.

00:34:12.358 --> 00:34:13.910
-Thank you.
-Bye-bye.

00:34:25.958 --> 00:34:28.252
All right, guys. Here we are in Jasper.

00:34:30.029 --> 00:34:31.222
How's Jasper?

00:34:31.289 --> 00:34:33.402
-Yeah, we like it.
-Are you both from here?

00:34:33.469 --> 00:34:36.443
-No. You're just traveling through?
-Yeah.

00:34:36.510 --> 00:34:37.683
-Is this your daughter?

00:34:37.750 --> 00:34:39.203
-Yes, it is.
-Okay.

00:34:39.270 --> 00:34:41.563
-What do you think of the Ozarks?
-Good!

00:34:41.630 --> 00:34:43.039
-They're good?
-We love it.

00:34:43.106 --> 00:34:44.923
-Yeah.
-You having a good time today?

00:34:44.990 --> 00:34:46.053
We're good.

00:34:46.120 --> 00:34:50.417
So I was reading the Buffalo River,
which you can't really see from the road.

00:34:50.484 --> 00:34:52.822
-But I was alongside it for a while.
-Right.

00:34:52.889 --> 00:34:56.309
It's a great American conservation story.

00:34:56.376 --> 00:34:59.744
Something like 132 miles
where it was never dammed.

00:34:59.811 --> 00:35:01.909
It's a free-flowing river.

00:35:01.976 --> 00:35:04.787
-Yeah, I've been down the river before.
-Is it sweet?

00:35:04.854 --> 00:35:08.080
It's been years when I was younger.

00:35:08.147 --> 00:35:11.178
I'm just cruising around.
I'm making a video of the Ozarks.

00:35:11.245 --> 00:35:15.065
Do you have anything else
you want to say about the Ozarks?

00:35:15.132 --> 00:35:16.045
No?

00:35:16.112 --> 00:35:17.631
I live with my dad.

00:35:17.698 --> 00:35:20.642
I was here a long time ago.

00:35:20.709 --> 00:35:23.068
-Yeah, you were.
-You were here a long time ago.

00:35:23.135 --> 00:35:24.950
Yeah, I grew up here.

00:35:25.017 --> 00:35:27.758
-Is it cool to come back this time?
-A whole lot.

00:35:27.825 --> 00:35:29.263
-Yeah.
-That's awesome.

00:35:29.330 --> 00:35:31.381
-See you both. Thank you.
-Yep.

00:35:32.676 --> 00:35:36.233
All right, guys. I think now is the time
to start Ann's elixir.

00:35:37.417 --> 00:35:38.711
With the instructions.

00:35:39.273 --> 00:35:41.072
You know, this is pure concentrate.

00:35:41.139 --> 00:35:44.167
What Ann says here at the bottom is

00:35:45.250 --> 00:35:46.720
you just want like.

00:35:47.350 --> 00:35:50.238
a tablespoon in here
with a fair amount of water.

00:35:50.714 --> 00:35:52.835
"Remember, poke is poisonous.

00:35:53.255 --> 00:35:56.482
Use responsibly and only as needed.

00:35:56.896 --> 00:35:59.578
Adult supervision for children."

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:02.730
[elixir swishing]

00:36:07.830 --> 00:36:11.242
Here we go. I'm gonna sip it
and follow it with some water.

00:36:15.583 --> 00:36:16.466
Whoa.

00:36:17.429 --> 00:36:18.508
That's intense.

00:36:19.870 --> 00:36:22.338
Okay, I understand why it's $15 now.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:26.381
Because a little bit goes a long way,

00:36:27.297 --> 00:36:28.352
as Ann said.

00:36:28.970 --> 00:36:32.264
Let's hope this doesn't cause problems
today on the road.

00:36:39.470 --> 00:36:40.353
Aah.

00:36:41.079 --> 00:36:41.962
Whew.

00:36:42.897 --> 00:36:44.779
Yeah, that's gonna do something.

00:36:45.241 --> 00:36:46.182
That's for sure.

00:36:50.443 --> 00:36:51.987
"Civil War in Newton County.

00:36:52.054 --> 00:36:55.704
Several military actions took place
in Newton County during the Civil War.

00:36:55.771 --> 00:36:59.898
January 10th, 1863,
Union troops attacked and destroyed

00:36:59.965 --> 00:37:03.158
a large saltpeter works
on the Buffalo River.

00:37:04.017 --> 00:37:07.645
Skirmishes were fought
June 14th, November 15th, 1863.

00:37:08.193 --> 00:37:10.708
April 17th, 1864.

00:37:10.775 --> 00:37:14.063
Scattering them and claiming
30 killed and 8 captured."

00:37:14.990 --> 00:37:16.990
Lot of history around these parts.

00:37:19.252 --> 00:37:20.135
Hi.

00:37:20.559 --> 00:37:22.556
And we got a cool looking place.

00:37:22.623 --> 00:37:23.743
Ozark Cafe.

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:27.992
Christian Motorcyclists Association.

00:37:29.022 --> 00:37:30.881
Is that nationwide or worldwide?

00:37:30.948 --> 00:37:32.029
[all] Worldwide.

00:37:32.395 --> 00:37:34.548
Good camaraderie or what's it all about?

00:37:34.615 --> 00:37:35.740
Yeah, it's good.

00:37:35.807 --> 00:37:39.064
Everything we do is for missions
and spreading the word.

00:37:39.131 --> 00:37:42.249
-Are people taking to the word
more these days or less?

00:37:43.300 --> 00:37:45.074
All depends on who you talk to.

00:37:45.141 --> 00:37:47.435
A lot of guys are willing to accept it.

00:37:47.834 --> 00:37:51.084
You get one once in a while that says,
I just don't believe in it.

00:37:51.151 --> 00:37:53.151
But most of the time, like this morning,

00:37:53.218 --> 00:37:55.647
I got to pray over six bikes and riders.

00:37:55.714 --> 00:37:56.997
-Nice. For their safety?

00:37:57.064 --> 00:38:00.989
Yes. Even the ones,
they won't accept prayer for themselves,

00:38:01.056 --> 00:38:03.143
they'll accept prayer for their bikes.

00:38:03.672 --> 00:38:05.420
Yep. Let's get a picture.

00:38:05.487 --> 00:38:08.553
-See the little camera down there?
-Where do you want me?

00:38:08.620 --> 00:38:12.385
I make videos all over the country.
It's on YouTube.

00:38:12.452 --> 00:38:15.349
Everything from the Amish
to the Bloods and Crips.

00:38:15.416 --> 00:38:16.945
And everything in between.

00:38:17.916 --> 00:38:21.059
You're right in the middle
of those two groups.

00:38:21.126 --> 00:38:23.231
He was probably a Blood back in the day.

00:38:23.305 --> 00:38:25.427
-But now he's on…
-[laughter]

00:38:25.494 --> 00:38:27.160
Now he's on the side of the Lord.

00:38:27.227 --> 00:38:30.698
You've heard people say
I'm a little rough around the edges.

00:38:31.749 --> 00:38:33.570
-You're Crips. Look at your blue.

00:38:33.637 --> 00:38:34.520
Yeah.

00:38:34.964 --> 00:38:38.812
We did church in Eureka Springs
at the Cat House for nine months.

00:38:38.879 --> 00:38:41.402
-Okay. At the Cat House?
-Yes, it's a bar.

00:38:41.469 --> 00:38:42.383
It's a bar.

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:45.123
-The girls wore dental floss.
-You did service there?

00:38:45.190 --> 00:38:47.003
We did it before they opened.

00:38:47.070 --> 00:38:48.778
We would pray with the girls.

00:38:48.845 --> 00:38:50.519
-I'll get in with you guys.

00:38:50.586 --> 00:38:52.563
I don't want to stand in front of you.

00:38:52.630 --> 00:38:54.992
Alright. Thanks you guys.

00:38:56.092 --> 00:38:57.326
Riding for the son.

00:38:57.393 --> 00:38:58.327
Today is our…

00:38:59.047 --> 00:39:00.165
Riding for the son.

00:39:01.471 --> 00:39:04.000
-Where we count all our donation money.
-Nice.

00:39:04.740 --> 00:39:07.790
Our chapter gathered $15,000.

00:39:07.857 --> 00:39:12.132
So we're gonna donate a motorcycle
to a pastor in a third world country.

00:39:12.199 --> 00:39:13.093
-Oh that's cool.

00:39:13.160 --> 00:39:15.253
So he can help spread the word.

00:39:15.320 --> 00:39:17.993
All the time it's not a motorcycle.

00:39:18.060 --> 00:39:20.033
Sometimes it's a boat, it's a bicycle.

00:39:20.100 --> 00:39:21.559
It's usually a motorcycle.

00:39:21.626 --> 00:39:23.642
Whatever they need to get the word out.

00:39:23.709 --> 00:39:25.970
-These roads are sweet for riding.
-Yeah.

00:39:26.037 --> 00:39:29.271
Actually the pavement
surprisingly is excellent.

00:39:30.092 --> 00:39:31.816
For Arkansas it's not bad.

00:39:31.883 --> 00:39:33.408
What I've seen so far.

00:39:33.488 --> 00:39:35.647
Better than we have up North.

00:39:35.714 --> 00:39:37.013
I'm from Michigan.

00:39:37.080 --> 00:39:39.254
Every secondary road is just terrible.

00:39:39.321 --> 00:39:40.697
-It's all beat up?

00:39:40.764 --> 00:39:43.203
He was a communist Canadian.

00:39:43.270 --> 00:39:44.862
-You let these union guys in?

00:39:44.929 --> 00:39:47.426
Yeah. Once in a while we make a pass.

00:39:48.326 --> 00:39:51.286
-I just became a US citizen last week.
-Are you serious?

00:39:51.353 --> 00:39:53.218
I've been here since 1972.

00:39:53.285 --> 00:39:55.344
-Congrats.
-Green card. I'm legal.

00:39:57.288 --> 00:39:58.501
They're white cards.

00:39:58.568 --> 00:40:02.631
You know my wife just had
her oath ceremony this last winter.

00:40:02.698 --> 00:40:03.639
It's a big deal.

00:40:04.403 --> 00:40:06.494
I haven't had the oath ceremony yet.

00:40:06.561 --> 00:40:08.313
-I'm past it.
-You're there.

00:40:08.967 --> 00:40:12.329
Another six weeks or so
we'll have our oath ceremony.

00:40:12.396 --> 00:40:14.543
-How does it feel?
-It feels awesome.

00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:17.818
We're from Michigan.
We've only been down here nine years.

00:40:17.885 --> 00:40:21.353
-What do you think of these Southern boys?
-We fell in love with them.

00:40:21.420 --> 00:40:23.949
Just gotta watch out for
this Canadian here.

00:40:24.884 --> 00:40:26.524
She's from Newfoundland.

00:40:26.591 --> 00:40:28.310
I picked her up hitchhiking.

00:40:28.377 --> 00:40:30.446
-Is that your lady?
-Yeah, that's my wife.

00:40:30.513 --> 00:40:32.184
-44 years.
-44 years.

00:40:32.251 --> 00:40:35.263
You met by picking her up hitchhiking?

00:40:35.330 --> 00:40:36.213
Yeah.

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:37.691
We got 20 grandkids.

00:40:38.253 --> 00:40:39.291
That's cool.

00:40:39.358 --> 00:40:42.869
I think I read this right.
This is a dry county, correct?

00:40:42.936 --> 00:40:43.819
This one is.

00:40:43.886 --> 00:40:45.576
-No alcohol for sale?
-Right.

00:40:45.643 --> 00:40:46.526
No bars?

00:40:47.002 --> 00:40:48.083
Newton County, huh-uh.

00:40:48.150 --> 00:40:52.515
You can just travel down the road
a little bit and find one that's not.

00:40:52.582 --> 00:40:55.237
People go over to the next county
to get their booze.

00:40:55.304 --> 00:40:56.544
-Come back?
-Yep.

00:40:56.611 --> 00:40:58.811
So that means
there are no bars in this town.

00:40:58.878 --> 00:40:59.761
-None.
-Nope.

00:40:59.828 --> 00:41:01.903
And you're also in Newton County.

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:05.971
You're in the only county in Arkansas
that doesn't have a single stoplight.

00:41:06.038 --> 00:41:06.921
Not one.

00:41:07.984 --> 00:41:08.994
In the whole county.

00:41:09.061 --> 00:41:11.873
So this is about as deep Ozark
as you can get, right?

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:14.458
Well, in Arkansas, yeah.

00:41:14.525 --> 00:41:16.792
I mean, you can go
a little further south but

00:41:16.859 --> 00:41:20.983
yeah, you're right in
the thick of it as far as Arkansas goes.

00:41:21.050 --> 00:41:24.780
-If you're part of CMA, you come into
a new town, you already got friends.

00:41:25.484 --> 00:41:27.407
We've got family all across the world.

00:41:27.474 --> 00:41:29.874
1,500 plus chapters
all across the United States.

00:41:29.941 --> 00:41:34.541
So like day one you're going out on a ride
and you got that common thread.

00:41:34.608 --> 00:41:35.863
-Absolutely.
-That's cool.

00:41:35.930 --> 00:41:39.475
I think we're shy of
200,000 people worldwide.

00:41:39.542 --> 00:41:40.963
Something like that, yeah.

00:41:41.030 --> 00:41:44.641
We stopped at noon today to pray
and at the same time.

00:41:45.064 --> 00:41:47.446
everybody else around the world
was stopped.

00:41:47.513 --> 00:41:48.851
-Are you serious?

00:41:48.925 --> 00:41:52.123
The whole CMA world
was stopping and praying today

00:41:52.190 --> 00:41:54.106
at the same time around the world.

00:41:54.173 --> 00:41:57.592
-But if it's noon here,
somewhere else it was 6:00 in afternoon.

00:41:57.659 --> 00:41:59.953
9:00 in the morning, 4:00 at night.

00:42:00.914 --> 00:42:02.720
Alaska was 9:00 AM.

00:42:04.198 --> 00:42:07.398
So it was 12:00 here, Eastern 1:00.

00:42:07.465 --> 00:42:08.936
So somewhere else it was…

00:42:10.879 --> 00:42:13.374
You can get on our website
and come ride with us.

00:42:13.441 --> 00:42:15.443
Changing the world one heart at a time.

00:42:15.510 --> 00:42:16.648
-Is it growing?

00:42:16.715 --> 00:42:17.915
-Yes.
-Oh, yes.

00:42:17.982 --> 00:42:19.352
Is it non-denominational?

00:42:19.419 --> 00:42:21.512
You gotta be Catholic or no?

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:25.529
Just believe Jesus died for our sins
so we can be saved.

00:42:25.596 --> 00:42:27.013
-And you're in?
-You're in.

00:42:27.080 --> 00:42:28.867
And we're not about the motorcycles.

00:42:28.934 --> 00:42:30.522
We just use that as a tool.

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:34.000
Because we're a ministry and not a club,

00:42:34.715 --> 00:42:38.155
a lot of the clubs
when you ride certain territories

00:42:38.222 --> 00:42:40.537
you have to ask permission
to go through there.

00:42:40.604 --> 00:42:42.218
-Territories.
-Yeah, territories.

00:42:42.285 --> 00:42:44.903
And ministry you don't. They respect…

00:42:44.970 --> 00:42:47.599
We're an association center of an MC.

00:42:47.666 --> 00:42:51.344
You'll find us at any
major motorcycle rally Laconia, Daytona.

00:42:52.397 --> 00:42:54.997
Sturgis or any of
the big rallies across the country.

00:42:55.070 --> 00:42:57.520
-You get along with the Hells Angels?
-We get along with all of them.

00:42:57.587 --> 00:42:59.668
Even with a name like Hell in their name?

00:42:59.735 --> 00:43:02.280
-Well, we're there to be a…
-[Peter laughs]

00:43:02.347 --> 00:43:04.443
Smart-a** question, sorry.

00:43:04.510 --> 00:43:07.171
Jesus came from Heaven
to Hell or to Earth

00:43:08.251 --> 00:43:09.166
to save sinners.

00:43:09.233 --> 00:43:11.233
-So you're good with everyone?

00:43:11.300 --> 00:43:12.393
Absolutely.

00:43:12.819 --> 00:43:15.063
Father in Jesus' name,
we just thank you for Peter

00:43:15.130 --> 00:43:18.135
and for this open door
that you've given us today, Lord God,

00:43:18.202 --> 00:43:20.979
that we're able to share the message
of Jesus Christ,

00:43:21.046 --> 00:43:25.076
that you came from Heaven to Earth
to seek and to save those which are lost.

00:43:25.143 --> 00:43:27.843
I don't know if Peter knows
you as his Lord and Savior,

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:31.210
but I speak blessings over Peter,
over his family, give him safety,

00:43:31.277 --> 00:43:33.841
traveling mercies, Lord God,
and keep him in the path

00:43:33.908 --> 00:43:36.121
that he needs to be in Jesus' name. Amen.

00:43:36.188 --> 00:43:38.127
-Amen.
-Amen. Thank you guys.

00:43:38.201 --> 00:43:39.084
Alright.

00:43:39.476 --> 00:43:42.064
-Appreciate you, Peter.
-Appreciate you, guys.

00:43:47.060 --> 00:43:48.723
Busy time of the year right now.

00:43:48.790 --> 00:43:50.956
40 miles east of Kansas City,

00:43:51.023 --> 00:43:54.848
but I come down to see
my great grandchild, son.

00:43:54.915 --> 00:43:56.276
-That's a great grandson?

00:43:56.343 --> 00:43:57.673
This is my grandson.

00:43:57.740 --> 00:44:01.342
Okay. But I got to see
my great grandson first time today.

00:44:01.861 --> 00:44:03.529
-Oh, how'd that feel?
-Great.

00:44:03.596 --> 00:44:04.932
[laughter]

00:44:04.999 --> 00:44:06.329
-It felt great, great?

00:44:06.396 --> 00:44:07.849
Yes, it did!

00:44:08.410 --> 00:44:12.811
Follow 7 up the mountain
and take a left on 374.

00:44:13.378 --> 00:44:14.891
Up at the top of the mountain.

00:44:14.958 --> 00:44:16.231
You'll get the real deal.

00:44:16.298 --> 00:44:17.258
You're laughing.

00:44:17.325 --> 00:44:19.793
There might be somebody you can talk to.

00:44:19.860 --> 00:44:22.477
So get to Vendor, hit some dirt roads.

00:44:22.544 --> 00:44:24.411
Yeah. Go cruise around through there.

00:44:24.478 --> 00:44:26.860
And they're not dirt, they're gravel.

00:44:26.927 --> 00:44:29.639
It looks like Georgia's orange color.

00:44:30.191 --> 00:44:33.303
You look like you've followed
a snake through a lot of it.

00:44:33.370 --> 00:44:36.403
There'll be potholes
you're gonna hit and bounce on.

00:44:37.633 --> 00:44:38.853
It's the real world.

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:41.063
-I want the real deal.
-There ya go.

00:44:41.719 --> 00:44:44.783
I've showed a lot of the nice stuff.
Now I'm ready to…

00:44:44.850 --> 00:44:45.920
-You'll enjoy it.

00:44:45.987 --> 00:44:48.311
-It's like a holler back there.
-Yep.

00:44:48.378 --> 00:44:51.606
Make sure you look at your map
before you get down in there

00:44:51.673 --> 00:44:54.674
because you are not gonna have service
once you get in there.

00:44:54.741 --> 00:44:56.676
And you probably won't, you know…

00:44:57.256 --> 00:44:59.393
-Populate your map.
-Okay.

00:45:00.216 --> 00:45:02.789
-Have a good day. Be careful.
-See you, guys.

00:45:04.476 --> 00:45:05.382
All right.

00:45:05.449 --> 00:45:08.742
I knew I wasn't really
seeing it today, guys.

00:45:08.809 --> 00:45:11.103
So look, we're covering a lot of ground.

00:45:12.744 --> 00:45:16.190
Not getting off on
every little road along the way.

00:45:16.257 --> 00:45:20.351
And they said go Vendor,
up into one of the hollers,

00:45:21.105 --> 00:45:24.270
and you'll see a different Ozarks.

00:45:25.107 --> 00:45:26.813
So that's what we're gonna do.

00:45:35.442 --> 00:45:37.658
We're finally getting a view of this place

00:45:37.725 --> 00:45:42.460
because most of the day
has been in the trees, in the valleys.

00:45:43.055 --> 00:45:44.983
And there's a reason for that.

00:45:45.050 --> 00:45:49.777
So it's interesting. Geologically,
instead of tectonic plates pushing upward,

00:45:49.844 --> 00:45:52.503
the landscape was formed
by millions of years of water

00:45:52.570 --> 00:45:54.703
eroding a flat plateau.

00:45:54.770 --> 00:45:58.713
So basically, this is the top
of the flat plateau right up here.

00:45:58.780 --> 00:46:03.038
And then years and years
of erosion brought the earth down

00:46:03.105 --> 00:46:05.827
and actually created the elevation.

00:46:05.894 --> 00:46:08.270
So quite different from
a lot of mountain ranges

00:46:08.337 --> 00:46:12.232
where those plates are coming together
and pushing the mountains up.

00:46:12.299 --> 00:46:14.903
I'm not a geologist,
but I thought that was cool.

00:46:14.970 --> 00:46:15.853
[country music]

00:46:28.172 --> 00:46:31.053
All right, guys. Just like
the locals said back in Jasper,

00:46:31.120 --> 00:46:33.710
get into Vendor, get on a dirt road,

00:46:34.243 --> 00:46:36.991
and you're gonna see a different Ozarks.

00:46:37.581 --> 00:46:39.440
I am quite surprised today, actually.

00:46:39.507 --> 00:46:41.795
I thought it was gonna be way more

00:46:42.520 --> 00:46:45.825
poor than, say, deep Appalachia.

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:47.605
Oh, that's beautiful.

00:46:48.052 --> 00:46:49.785
Look at that. That's beautiful.

00:46:49.852 --> 00:46:52.602
Nice, clear, clean water.

00:46:53.010 --> 00:46:56.814
So yeah, I was thinking it was gonna be
way more blown out looking,

00:46:58.380 --> 00:47:02.699
and poor than Appalachia
because they have the strong mining past.

00:47:02.766 --> 00:47:04.531
Coal is still happening there.

00:47:04.940 --> 00:47:06.943
There are some good paying jobs.

00:47:07.010 --> 00:47:08.763
Of course, it's not what it was.

00:47:08.830 --> 00:47:11.124
But I was told the Ozarks are just like…

00:47:11.554 --> 00:47:14.900
I mean, we're looking at
a Tesla back here in the holler.

00:47:17.003 --> 00:47:20.146
So I thought it was gonna be
much poorer than…

00:47:20.750 --> 00:47:23.216
Whoa! I think we're at someone's house.

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:25.313
Oops.

00:47:25.380 --> 00:47:26.298
[dog barking]

00:47:29.745 --> 00:47:30.873
Okay, here we go.

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:33.593
That was the driveway. This is the road.

00:47:34.366 --> 00:47:39.026
So, what I was saying is I thought it was
gonna be much worse off economically.

00:47:39.093 --> 00:47:40.851
At least in appearance.

00:47:40.918 --> 00:47:44.426
You know, like more blown out things
than deep Appalachia.

00:47:44.493 --> 00:47:45.833
It's been the opposite.

00:47:45.900 --> 00:47:47.884
The regions have some similarities.

00:47:47.951 --> 00:47:51.371
You know, they're a Scottish, Irish,

00:47:51.937 --> 00:47:53.289
ethnic origin here.

00:47:53.848 --> 00:47:57.043
A lot of this stuff,
deep treed-in hillsides.

00:47:57.110 --> 00:48:00.736
I think sort of traditionally a similar

00:48:01.226 --> 00:48:03.860
self-reliance element to these places.

00:48:03.927 --> 00:48:07.398
People wanting to get away
from everything, be on their own.

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:12.691
And so there are those common grounds,
but there is a much different feel.

00:48:13.225 --> 00:48:16.031
Everything is what you're used to.

00:48:16.098 --> 00:48:20.721
And so when I'm thinking of a rough holler,
this is not my definition of it at all.

00:48:21.149 --> 00:48:23.856
This is actually sort of nice.

00:48:25.240 --> 00:48:28.465
I was reading last night
about the bushwhacker era here.

00:48:28.910 --> 00:48:30.918
Which, from my understanding,

00:48:30.985 --> 00:48:33.525
it was full-on guerrilla warfare.

00:48:33.592 --> 00:48:38.163
As in neighbors ransacking
and burning down neighbors' houses,

00:48:38.750 --> 00:48:40.932
intercounty conflicts, that sort of thing.

00:48:40.999 --> 00:48:43.705
Now, I don't know
if that applies to all of the Ozarks,

00:48:43.772 --> 00:48:48.591
but some of these far out regions,
just so far from the government

00:48:49.378 --> 00:48:52.420
that things were
handled locally many a times.

00:48:52.487 --> 00:48:55.998
There was no centralized control out here.

00:48:56.071 --> 00:48:59.465
So the bushwhackers,
the Southern sympathizers,

00:48:59.851 --> 00:49:03.596
and the Jayhawkers,
the Northern sympathizers,

00:49:03.663 --> 00:49:07.983
encouraged a cycle of executions
and house burnings and

00:49:08.050 --> 00:49:12.707
internal town and county level
feuds going on.

00:49:12.774 --> 00:49:14.427
People turned on each other here.

00:49:14.494 --> 00:49:18.260
Just depending on what side they were on

00:49:18.773 --> 00:49:19.787
in those times.

00:49:20.273 --> 00:49:21.849
So, very rogue.

00:49:21.916 --> 00:49:24.439
Very much on their own out here.

00:49:24.506 --> 00:49:26.771
And you get a feel once you're out here.

00:49:27.159 --> 00:49:30.190
You know, today I have
the camera off most of the time, guys.

00:49:30.257 --> 00:49:33.049
Because I've been driving all day.
What is it, 3:00?

00:49:33.116 --> 00:49:35.043
Been driving since 8:00 this morning.

00:49:35.110 --> 00:49:37.354
It's a huge amount of territory.

00:49:37.421 --> 00:49:38.304
It's like

00:49:38.820 --> 00:49:42.713
another America that I had no idea existed.

00:49:42.780 --> 00:49:44.850
Obviously, I heard of the Ozarks.

00:49:44.917 --> 00:49:47.372
But I honestly thought more of lakes.

00:49:47.439 --> 00:49:51.008
When I heard Ozarks,
I was thinking Lake of the Ozarks.

00:49:51.075 --> 00:49:52.689
I think like a lot of us.

00:49:52.756 --> 00:49:55.168
And what a great Netflix series that was.

00:49:55.892 --> 00:49:58.500
But then more commonly
are the Ozark mountains.

00:49:58.567 --> 00:50:00.777
That's what most people
think of around here.

00:50:00.844 --> 00:50:04.307
When you hear the word Ozark,
what do you think?

00:50:04.374 --> 00:50:05.933
And they said mountains.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:10.081
So as an outsider,
I thought it was more about the lakes.

00:50:10.148 --> 00:50:14.343
Now, lake of the Ozark is north of here
over the border in Missouri.

00:50:14.410 --> 00:50:16.519
So those are Ozarks also.

00:50:16.586 --> 00:50:20.788
But this massive territory,
what a surprise.

00:50:21.255 --> 00:50:26.092
You could spend weeks and months
exploring all of these nooks and crannies.

00:50:26.567 --> 00:50:27.633
[music continues]

00:50:45.252 --> 00:50:49.133
…to get to Snowball from here
through Richland Creek.

00:50:49.805 --> 00:50:51.798
Richland Creek… That's my wife.

00:50:52.738 --> 00:50:53.968
Richland Creek,

00:50:55.335 --> 00:50:57.613
in this car, you're not gonna make it.

00:50:57.680 --> 00:50:58.584
-Are you serious?

00:50:58.651 --> 00:51:01.773
Yeah. It's a rocky creek
and it's probably about 50 yards wide.

00:51:01.840 --> 00:51:03.664
-There's no bridge over it?
-No.

00:51:04.490 --> 00:51:06.383
I'm not gonna make it out here.

00:51:06.450 --> 00:51:08.360
-Not this way, you're not.
-Oh, man.

00:51:08.427 --> 00:51:09.755
I've got to turn around?

00:51:09.822 --> 00:51:12.388
So what you're gonna have to do
is go back this way,

00:51:12.455 --> 00:51:14.573
get your way back out to Highway 65,

00:51:14.950 --> 00:51:17.103
and take Highway 65 east.

00:51:17.170 --> 00:51:18.350
-How far out is that?

00:51:18.417 --> 00:51:20.518
Oh, it's probably 30 minutes from here.

00:51:20.585 --> 00:51:23.543
-Ah, jeez. I just came from there.
-[laughs] Yeah.

00:51:23.610 --> 00:51:26.898
-You grew up in Southeastern Arkansas?
-Right.

00:51:26.965 --> 00:51:29.448
And you sold the land to who?

00:51:29.515 --> 00:51:33.149
My grandpa actually leased it
to the Arkansas State Penitentiary

00:51:34.074 --> 00:51:37.439
back in the days when the inmates
actually worked on the farm.

00:51:37.506 --> 00:51:39.569
Nowadays, you can't make them do that.

00:51:39.636 --> 00:51:41.654
And they can't be called a penitentiary.

00:51:41.721 --> 00:51:45.309
They had to change it to
"Arkansas Department of Corrections."

00:51:45.804 --> 00:51:48.141
-They can't do the farm work anymore?
-No.

00:51:48.208 --> 00:51:49.852
It's against their civil rights.

00:51:49.919 --> 00:51:53.953
They don't get out there anymore
with their hoes. But it was hard work.

00:51:54.020 --> 00:51:55.302
-It was.
-Yeah.

00:51:55.369 --> 00:51:58.549
I remember as a kid
I grew up in Southeast Arkansas

00:51:58.983 --> 00:52:00.708
until I was about 11 years old.

00:52:01.169 --> 00:52:04.609
To get to my house,
you had to drive along this bayou.

00:52:05.028 --> 00:52:07.725
At times, you would see
the prisoners out there.

00:52:07.792 --> 00:52:12.863
Of course, you know, you had guards
on their horses watching them.

00:52:12.930 --> 00:52:15.693
But you'd see prisoners
out there waist deep

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:17.500
digging stumps out of that bayou.

00:52:17.567 --> 00:52:19.539
Pulling cotton or working in the field.

00:52:19.606 --> 00:52:21.162
-You guys aren't even that old.

00:52:21.229 --> 00:52:24.347
-I'm 62.
-I am 55.

00:52:24.414 --> 00:52:28.115
And as a child, I can remember
looking across the road from my house

00:52:28.182 --> 00:52:30.868
and seeing them work in the field.

00:52:30.935 --> 00:52:33.347
-Okay. So what made you guys move up here?

00:52:34.013 --> 00:52:37.524
My mom and dad, we left down there
just for personal stuff.

00:52:37.939 --> 00:52:41.001
And we moved up to
a little town called Paris,

00:52:41.068 --> 00:52:42.948
which is down in the river valley.

00:52:43.015 --> 00:52:45.543
And I grew up the rest of my life there.

00:52:45.610 --> 00:52:47.413
-Retired from the military.
-Yeah.

00:52:47.480 --> 00:52:48.787
Oh, thank you.

00:52:48.854 --> 00:52:50.163
Yeah, 34 years of service.

00:52:50.230 --> 00:52:53.192
And then you guys just decided
to get up in the sticks here.

00:52:53.259 --> 00:52:55.593
We actually dated when we were younger.

00:52:55.660 --> 00:52:57.824
-And reconnected after 40 years.
-Yeah.

00:52:58.811 --> 00:53:00.215
Did anything change?

00:53:00.282 --> 00:53:03.681
A lot, yeah. I was a brat. I was spoiled.

00:53:03.748 --> 00:53:05.973
She's still spoiled
but I liked her that way.

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:09.071
-I had dumped him and it was like…
-You dumped him?!

00:53:09.558 --> 00:53:10.925
-Oh, she did.
-I did.

00:53:10.992 --> 00:53:12.549
You went back. You kept trying.

00:53:12.616 --> 00:53:16.321
After 40 years, he had a Bronco
that he had when we dated.

00:53:16.388 --> 00:53:17.610
Old '71 Bronco.

00:53:17.677 --> 00:53:21.509
And he posted it on Facebook
and that caused us to start a conversation.

00:53:21.970 --> 00:53:24.489
And then we decided to meet,
and then here I am.

00:53:24.556 --> 00:53:27.284
I sold my house in South Louisiana
and moved back home.

00:53:27.351 --> 00:53:30.953
-Wow. So this part of the state…
We are out there right now.

00:53:31.020 --> 00:53:32.838
-Yeah.
-We are so out there.

00:53:32.905 --> 00:53:35.905
-Let's put it this way…
-We're gonna put a house right there.

00:53:35.972 --> 00:53:36.855
Sweet.

00:53:36.922 --> 00:53:39.713
Here's how I put everything
in perspective for people.

00:53:39.780 --> 00:53:43.434
Like, there's a bank on every corner
in town and everything, you know?

00:53:43.507 --> 00:53:48.101
Well, in Arkansas, there's a Dollar General
on almost every corner. Right?

00:53:48.168 --> 00:53:49.673
I haven't seen one today.

00:53:49.740 --> 00:53:52.517
-Oh, come on.
-'Cause I've been to deep Ozarks all day.

00:53:52.584 --> 00:53:53.530
Oh, wow.

00:53:53.597 --> 00:53:55.611
-Well, for us…
-The closest one is what?

00:53:55.678 --> 00:53:57.889
-30 minutes away.
-30 minutes away. You know.

00:53:57.956 --> 00:53:59.908
The nearest Walmart is an hour away.

00:53:59.975 --> 00:54:01.506
And for Arkansas, that's huge.

00:54:01.573 --> 00:54:03.897
Yeah.
You have to make your trips count. So…

00:54:03.964 --> 00:54:07.333
Okay. But why? You just want to be
away from people, get in nature?

00:54:07.400 --> 00:54:09.814
Yeah. I'll be honest with you, you know,

00:54:09.881 --> 00:54:13.359
and this might rub some people
the wrong way, but society today.

00:54:14.090 --> 00:54:15.267
-You're not feeling it?

00:54:15.334 --> 00:54:18.879
When you stop, you don't hear traffic,
you don't hear noise.

00:54:19.246 --> 00:54:21.345
-The only…
-It's peaceful.

00:54:21.412 --> 00:54:23.659
The only thing we get around here is like,

00:54:24.149 --> 00:54:26.464
no offense,
people like you, traveling through.

00:54:26.531 --> 00:54:28.733
-Look… Which is awesome.
-Curiosity.

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:31.536
And there'll be…
We get a lot of motorcycles.

00:54:31.603 --> 00:54:32.486
-Okay.

00:54:32.554 --> 00:54:33.733
Street and trail bikes.

00:54:34.272 --> 00:54:37.893
This three acres here was completely…

00:54:37.960 --> 00:54:40.088
It was covered. It was thick.

00:54:40.155 --> 00:54:42.183
I hired somebody
to come and clean it up.

00:54:42.250 --> 00:54:45.353
There was an old house here
and it had been here for a while.

00:54:45.420 --> 00:54:51.380
This house actually used to
belong to the head guy of the KKK.

00:54:51.447 --> 00:54:53.877
-Are you serious?
-Yeah, he started the KKK.

00:54:54.375 --> 00:54:56.309
-So that was huge out here?

00:54:56.395 --> 00:54:58.795
Oh, yeah. Harrison. It was big.

00:54:58.862 --> 00:55:00.063
-Really? Okay.

00:55:00.130 --> 00:55:01.855
That's the headquarters.

00:55:01.922 --> 00:55:03.483
-No way. Right here?

00:55:03.550 --> 00:55:05.508
-Right here.
-That is wild. Okay.

00:55:05.575 --> 00:55:07.330
Didn't expect that coming.

00:55:07.397 --> 00:55:09.343
-Are those guys still around?
-No.

00:55:10.029 --> 00:55:11.612
You don't… I mean…

00:55:11.679 --> 00:55:14.194
It probably is
but it's nothing like it used to be.

00:55:14.261 --> 00:55:16.641
They're way underground?
A few of them probably?

00:55:16.708 --> 00:55:19.228
-I don't know.
-It's pretty outspoken in Harrison.

00:55:19.295 --> 00:55:22.450
-What?
-It used to be. The KKK. It used to be.

00:55:22.880 --> 00:55:25.644
But you don't really hear
anybody talk about it anymore.

00:55:25.711 --> 00:55:28.717
-That's wild.
I didn't even think of that today.

00:55:28.784 --> 00:55:30.625
I didn't even think about that.

00:55:30.692 --> 00:55:33.937
The main man, the head of it,
used to live right here.

00:55:34.004 --> 00:55:35.266
-[Peter] Whew!
-[giggling]

00:55:35.333 --> 00:55:37.445
-How's that make you feel?
-Kind of creepy.

00:55:37.512 --> 00:55:41.286
When I first found out about it,
I didn't know when I bought the property.

00:55:41.360 --> 00:55:43.538
We found out about it
like six months later.

00:55:43.605 --> 00:55:45.833
I had a local guy tell me.

00:55:45.900 --> 00:55:50.306
He said, "Me and my dad laid the brick
for the chimney in that house."

00:55:50.373 --> 00:55:52.283
And I said, oh yeah? He said, yeah.

00:55:52.350 --> 00:55:55.473
The guy that owned it at that time
was the head of the KKK.

00:55:55.540 --> 00:55:57.900
-And I said shut up.
-[chuckling]

00:55:57.967 --> 00:56:00.501
-We had no idea.
-He said, yeah, seriously.

00:56:00.568 --> 00:56:01.777
He was a young man then.

00:56:01.844 --> 00:56:04.565
Did you get a real low price or something?

00:56:04.632 --> 00:56:08.363
Well, let me tell you what,
in this area before COVID,

00:56:08.430 --> 00:56:11.322
you could buy land in this area for,

00:56:11.789 --> 00:56:15.095
-it depends on what shape it was in…
-[truck roars past]

00:56:16.568 --> 00:56:19.861
But you could get it for,
you know, just under $2,000.

00:56:19.928 --> 00:56:21.153
-An acre?
-An acre. Yeah.

00:56:21.220 --> 00:56:22.125
Not anymore.

00:56:22.192 --> 00:56:24.533
Which was, you know, it's a decent price.

00:56:24.600 --> 00:56:28.910
Now, the average going, I mean,
just for something like this,

00:56:29.583 --> 00:56:31.345
and mind you, it was covered up.

00:56:31.412 --> 00:56:33.829
When you drove by it,
you was like, I don't know.

00:56:33.896 --> 00:56:37.663
-When he first presented it to me,
I was like, no, I just didn't see it.

00:56:37.730 --> 00:56:40.333
-I couldn't see it.
-But now, average price is about…

00:56:40.400 --> 00:56:43.334
For an area like this,
it's like $5,000 an acre.

00:56:43.401 --> 00:56:44.284
-Okay.

00:56:44.351 --> 00:56:46.908
But you get people living in California

00:56:47.476 --> 00:56:49.257
where they're selling their…

00:56:49.324 --> 00:56:52.710
What we have a home here
that goes for, say,

00:56:53.277 --> 00:56:57.088
$150,000 is selling for
over a million dollars there.

00:56:57.580 --> 00:56:59.051
Well, they're coming here

00:56:59.552 --> 00:57:01.006
and buying a lot,

00:57:02.118 --> 00:57:04.411
you know, just a lot of land.

00:57:04.478 --> 00:57:06.765
-Not even an acre.
-For $30,000, $40,000.

00:57:07.257 --> 00:57:10.102
And that's over on Highway 7,
Scenic Highway 7.

00:57:10.169 --> 00:57:13.673
-Okay. So the locals who are selling
are like, oh, we're banking here.

00:57:13.740 --> 00:57:14.794
A lot of them are.

00:57:14.861 --> 00:57:16.933
-He went out literally to check the mail.

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:20.863
And the guy that owns this place was
coming down the road and they're talking.

00:57:20.930 --> 00:57:22.393
I said, what are you doing?

00:57:22.460 --> 00:57:25.069
He said, I just bought the place next door.

00:57:25.136 --> 00:57:26.799
I'm gonna get my checkbook.

00:57:26.866 --> 00:57:29.421
And it literally happened
at the end of the driveway

00:57:29.488 --> 00:57:31.058
while he was checking the mail.

00:57:31.125 --> 00:57:33.628
-That is a wild story.
-Yeah.

00:57:34.050 --> 00:57:36.748
What you see is just,
I guess, I don't know,

00:57:36.815 --> 00:57:38.310
just the face of everything.

00:57:38.377 --> 00:57:39.260
Yeah.

00:57:39.920 --> 00:57:41.624
You go out into these woods

00:57:42.790 --> 00:57:44.437
and you see old home places,

00:57:44.977 --> 00:57:48.007
you know, where flowers are growing up.

00:57:48.074 --> 00:57:49.458
Where houses used to be.

00:57:49.525 --> 00:57:53.498
You can find lilies that are growing up
out in the middle of the woods

00:57:53.565 --> 00:57:55.511
from old home places around here.

00:57:55.578 --> 00:57:58.952
-So I heard back in the day
in Civil War times,

00:57:59.697 --> 00:58:01.817
you're either with the North or the South.

00:58:01.884 --> 00:58:04.543
And they were like neighbors
going at each other.

00:58:04.986 --> 00:58:07.599
-That was a thing, huh?
-Oh, absolutely. Around here.

00:58:07.666 --> 00:58:10.963
A lot of these foundations you see
might just be from that time.

00:58:11.030 --> 00:58:12.730
-Who knows?
-Oh, yeah, before that.

00:58:12.797 --> 00:58:14.790
A lot are before the Civil War.

00:58:14.857 --> 00:58:16.857
What are people doing for work out here?

00:58:16.924 --> 00:58:20.588
Well, I mean,
if you don't have your own business…

00:58:20.655 --> 00:58:21.563
Or retired.

00:58:21.630 --> 00:58:25.376
You have a lot of loggers
and people have sawmills.

00:58:25.443 --> 00:58:26.615
-Okay.
-Stuff like that.

00:58:26.682 --> 00:58:29.738
But I mean, if you don't have
something of your own business,

00:58:29.805 --> 00:58:32.782
a lot of people,
they travel out like into Harrison.

00:58:32.849 --> 00:58:35.453
They have to go like an hour or so.

00:58:35.520 --> 00:58:37.094
Our neighbor works remotely.

00:58:37.161 --> 00:58:38.742
To Harrison or to Russellville.

00:58:38.809 --> 00:58:40.793
I work remotely. He has retirement.

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:43.633
So you find some people
who have remote jobs.

00:58:43.700 --> 00:58:46.113
Okay. So then there are not
many kids out here?

00:58:46.180 --> 00:58:47.793
-Not many.
-No.

00:58:47.890 --> 00:58:50.123
-You probably came through Mount Judy.
-Yep.

00:58:50.200 --> 00:58:53.290
This school probably has 150 kids.

00:58:53.357 --> 00:58:57.239
Let's say they're graduating class
this year may have been 10 kids.

00:58:58.100 --> 00:59:01.554
Today's a great day where it's like
if you turn on the television

00:59:01.621 --> 00:59:02.983
or look online, right?

00:59:03.050 --> 00:59:06.350
The media, the politicians,
they're pitting us against one another.

00:59:06.417 --> 00:59:07.300
Right.

00:59:07.367 --> 00:59:10.323
I get on the road,
nothing but smiles and people are cool.

00:59:10.390 --> 00:59:13.093
There's an a-hole every,
you know, you run into them.

00:59:13.160 --> 00:59:16.197
When I hear like, oh, civil war,
it's just the dumbest thing

00:59:16.264 --> 00:59:19.838
'cause I don't care who you voted for
and most people don't give a sh*t.

00:59:19.905 --> 00:59:21.505
-Right. I don't care.
-I don't think.

00:59:21.572 --> 00:59:22.946
If you're cool to someone…

00:59:23.013 --> 00:59:27.338
That's my neighbor down here,
she's full-blood Democrat, you know?

00:59:27.405 --> 00:59:29.909
And she hates Trump and all this and that.

00:59:29.976 --> 00:59:32.132
-But you know what?
-I love her to death.

00:59:32.199 --> 00:59:34.049
-That's cool.
-She's a good old woman.

00:59:34.116 --> 00:59:36.563
-You know, I take care of her.
-He mows her yard.

00:59:36.630 --> 00:59:39.495
-That's how it should be.
-But we don't talk politics.

00:59:39.576 --> 00:59:42.093
I'm not gonna let that stuff
come between me and you.

00:59:42.160 --> 00:59:43.133
That's smart.

00:59:43.200 --> 00:59:44.526
I best be on my way, guys.

00:59:44.593 --> 00:59:45.652
-All right.
-Peter…

00:59:46.352 --> 00:59:48.269
Man, it was good meeting you, dude.

00:59:48.336 --> 00:59:50.021
-Absolutely.
-[laughter]

00:59:50.088 --> 00:59:51.275
That's a good one.

00:59:51.342 --> 00:59:52.695
I won't do that to you.

01:00:00.393 --> 01:00:02.217
[Peter] How are you doing, sir?

01:00:02.619 --> 01:00:04.836
-How's the food here?
-Pretty good.

01:00:04.903 --> 01:00:06.260
-Pretty good?
-Yep.

01:00:06.327 --> 01:00:07.772
It's the only thing in town.

01:00:07.839 --> 01:00:09.971
Yep. The only thing in town.

01:00:12.806 --> 01:00:14.512
[old timey banjo music plays]

01:00:20.016 --> 01:00:21.386
Wow, this is cool.

01:00:23.690 --> 01:00:24.890
"Hillbilly Slims"

01:00:31.009 --> 01:00:33.231
[woman] …burnt a couple years back.

01:00:33.298 --> 01:00:35.812
-The whole place burnt a couple years back?

01:00:35.879 --> 01:00:41.479
It had a bad storm that night
and it hit one of the transformers.

01:00:41.546 --> 01:00:42.435
-Oh!

01:00:42.502 --> 01:00:44.202
It sailed through the whole thing.

01:00:44.269 --> 01:00:48.157
And at the time, we had
a woodworking shop in the back of it.

01:00:48.224 --> 01:00:49.107
-Okay.

01:00:49.174 --> 01:00:52.271
And so, as soon as it hit that,
all the lacquer,

01:00:52.338 --> 01:00:55.098
and Sawdust, and wood, just…

01:00:55.165 --> 01:00:56.106
-It just blew up?

01:00:56.879 --> 01:00:59.589
-So this is all new?
-Yep. All new.

01:01:05.606 --> 01:01:06.489
All right guys,

01:01:07.699 --> 01:01:10.142
I rate the pulled pork sandwich.

01:01:11.784 --> 01:01:12.772
super tender pork,

01:01:13.870 --> 01:01:16.203
soft, not dried out at all.

01:01:20.012 --> 01:01:22.152
I'll give that a nine.

01:01:23.172 --> 01:01:25.220
But I'm no food critic at all.

01:01:26.523 --> 01:01:27.464
But that's good.

01:01:28.374 --> 01:01:30.267
And it is just so cool today.

01:01:30.940 --> 01:01:32.352
One thing I want to say.

01:01:32.982 --> 01:01:36.388
You know, usually I think of
places like Arizona or Montana.

01:01:37.546 --> 01:01:41.525
Those big open road trips, right?
Where you just get lost on the road.

01:01:42.678 --> 01:01:45.500
You don't see things
for a long period of time.

01:01:45.567 --> 01:01:48.774
And while Arkansas is its own thing

01:01:48.841 --> 01:01:51.363
and things are tighter here
and more treed-in,

01:01:51.956 --> 01:01:55.351
it almost has that epic road trip feel.

01:01:55.418 --> 01:01:57.774
Actually, it does have
that epic road trip feel.

01:01:57.841 --> 01:01:58.867
Today it was like,

01:01:59.495 --> 01:02:00.378
I don't know,

01:02:01.101 --> 01:02:05.108
six hours constantly driving at least.

01:02:06.133 --> 01:02:08.833
And you stop in the small town
and people want to talk.

01:02:08.900 --> 01:02:11.447
The people here are fantastic.
They're so cool.

01:02:11.937 --> 01:02:14.733
Stop in the town, talk to people,

01:02:15.479 --> 01:02:16.571
hit the open road,

01:02:17.350 --> 01:02:18.233
see the…

01:02:18.698 --> 01:02:20.815
Absorb the beautiful nature.

01:02:22.043 --> 01:02:25.258
And it's awesome. I'm working.
I gotta get the video to you guys.

01:02:25.325 --> 01:02:27.543
So I gotta talk to people,
find the stories.

01:02:27.610 --> 01:02:30.934
I'm constantly looking like
what's gonna be interesting to show.

01:02:31.001 --> 01:02:33.101
So it's not like
I'm relaxed and chilling.

01:02:33.470 --> 01:02:36.128
But if you come out
to this part of the country,

01:02:36.195 --> 01:02:39.798
just got some time
and car in the open road,

01:02:41.217 --> 01:02:42.424
it is so cool.

01:02:42.491 --> 01:02:44.373
There's nothing better, I think.

01:02:46.103 --> 01:02:50.635
And the reason I always
support these businesses

01:02:50.702 --> 01:02:52.574
in these videos, small businesses,

01:02:52.641 --> 01:02:54.438
is because without them,

01:02:55.225 --> 01:02:59.161
we just have chains,
and there's soul in this,

01:02:59.228 --> 01:03:02.942
and there's someone's livelihood,
a local family's livelihood most likely.

01:03:03.009 --> 01:03:04.888
I don't know the guy,

01:03:04.955 --> 01:03:09.060
but I always like to try to promote
these places because without them,

01:03:09.127 --> 01:03:11.444
they don't really have
any cool places to stop.

01:03:11.511 --> 01:03:13.387
I don't get too excited about chains.

01:03:13.454 --> 01:03:15.317
So I know a lot of you don't either.

01:03:15.384 --> 01:03:19.761
That's the reason I drop these links.
I'll drop this link in the description.

01:03:19.828 --> 01:03:23.251
And again,
I don't know this guy, zero affiliation.

01:03:23.941 --> 01:03:26.470
But hey, respect
to anyone trying to make it

01:03:27.054 --> 01:03:28.668
especially in food and beverage.

01:03:28.735 --> 01:03:31.165
Like this is not easy
look at this location.

01:03:32.505 --> 01:03:34.499
We're in the middle of nowhere.

01:03:34.566 --> 01:03:38.684
Like how many cars
have passed since I've sat down?

01:03:38.751 --> 01:03:39.986
I don't know. One?

01:03:40.803 --> 01:03:43.215
And it's gotta be hard

01:03:44.138 --> 01:03:46.268
hiring people, getting food out here.

01:03:46.335 --> 01:03:47.815
This is a huge facility.

01:03:47.882 --> 01:03:51.001
I'm sure they got their busy times,
but mid summer, mid winter,

01:03:51.068 --> 01:03:52.715
I'm sure it's ghostly quiet.

01:03:53.314 --> 01:03:55.914
So always want to support local businesses

01:03:55.981 --> 01:03:59.556
if I think they're good,
this is a good sandwich, so it's worth it.

01:03:59.623 --> 01:04:00.506
[country music]

01:04:24.745 --> 01:04:26.389
We have old Snowball here.

01:04:27.218 --> 01:04:28.336
Look at this place.

01:04:33.007 --> 01:04:34.989
Look at that old drink vending machine.

01:04:35.720 --> 01:04:38.418
That thing is ancient. Wow.

01:04:39.845 --> 01:04:45.258
Snowball. So the locals
meant to call this place Snow Hall

01:04:45.720 --> 01:04:48.518
after Sheriff Benjamin Franklin Snow.

01:04:48.585 --> 01:04:50.713
But when they petitioned
for a post office,

01:04:50.780 --> 01:04:54.684
 the name was reportedly
misread as Snowball.

01:04:55.260 --> 01:04:59.453
The post office operated until 1966.

01:05:00.128 --> 01:05:01.318
So they say.

01:05:01.385 --> 01:05:04.693
So the Internet says.
But this is still open, I heard.

01:05:05.207 --> 01:05:08.091
I talked to a guy off camera
a few towns over

01:05:08.158 --> 01:05:12.196
and he said they still have
the Mason's Lodge functioning.

01:05:13.080 --> 01:05:14.689
"4th Saturday 7:00."

01:05:15.880 --> 01:05:17.292
[Peter] Are you a Mason?

01:05:17.787 --> 01:05:18.670
-No.
-No.

01:05:20.012 --> 01:05:21.923
I live here but I'm not…

01:05:21.990 --> 01:05:23.658
-What's your name?
-Alan.

01:05:23.725 --> 01:05:24.758
Alan. Peter.

01:05:24.825 --> 01:05:26.605
Now right there is…

01:05:27.111 --> 01:05:28.373
Good pressure.

01:05:28.440 --> 01:05:31.028
They don't shake hands that hard.

01:05:32.084 --> 01:05:35.014
-They're really weak.
-The Masons shake really weak?

01:05:35.081 --> 01:05:36.596
-Come here.
-How do they shake?

01:05:36.663 --> 01:05:38.663
-Just relax your hands.
-All right.

01:05:41.470 --> 01:05:43.916
-It's not my type of shake.
-It's limp.

01:05:45.046 --> 01:05:47.879
She's got a better… You're a Mason?

01:05:47.946 --> 01:05:50.767
-No.
-You're not a Mason. Mason are men.

01:05:50.834 --> 01:05:52.596
-She cannot be a Mason.
-I can't be.

01:05:52.663 --> 01:05:55.403
Okay what's going 
on in Snowball these days?

01:05:55.470 --> 01:05:59.505
We have an adventure race next weekend.

01:05:59.572 --> 01:06:02.868
-Running race?
-You run to the river.

01:06:02.935 --> 01:06:05.714
-Yep.
-Kayak to Tyler Bend.

01:06:05.781 --> 01:06:06.664
-Nice.

01:06:06.731 --> 01:06:08.733
And ride your bicycle back here.

01:06:08.800 --> 01:06:10.367
It's cool community out here?

01:06:10.863 --> 01:06:13.411
And that's basically it.
You know what I mean?

01:06:13.867 --> 01:06:15.606
-Everyone knows everyone?

01:06:16.026 --> 01:06:16.949
Yeah.

01:06:17.016 --> 01:06:19.242
They know what you're doing
before you even do it.

01:06:19.309 --> 01:06:21.897
You know Arkansas
from what I've seen so far,

01:06:22.360 --> 01:06:24.125
it's like different countries.

01:06:24.694 --> 01:06:26.823
I was in Bentonville this morning.

01:06:26.890 --> 01:06:28.770
That's like another country.

01:06:28.837 --> 01:06:31.537
I was in Pine Bluff.
That's like another country.

01:06:31.604 --> 01:06:35.663
Yeah.
Yeah it's definitely another country.

01:06:37.147 --> 01:06:41.326
And now I'm out in the Ozarks
and I had no idea they were so big.

01:06:41.936 --> 01:06:43.618
I've been driving all day.

01:06:43.685 --> 01:06:46.164
And I haven't even gotten across them yet.

01:06:46.231 --> 01:06:48.761
I was trying to get to
Mountain View before sundown

01:06:48.828 --> 01:06:50.651
but I don't think I'm gonna do it.

01:06:50.719 --> 01:06:53.182
-It's a couple hours.
-A couple hours still?

01:06:53.639 --> 01:06:54.711
Jeez.

01:06:54.778 --> 01:06:56.219
Did you guys grew up here?

01:06:56.279 --> 01:06:57.200
-Uh he did.

01:06:57.267 --> 01:06:58.263
-I…

01:06:58.330 --> 01:07:02.266
I have lived like a mile
from here in my life.

01:07:02.961 --> 01:07:04.549
How was it growing up here?

01:07:04.990 --> 01:07:06.166
That was great here.

01:07:07.620 --> 01:07:08.808
There is no crime.

01:07:09.476 --> 01:07:10.359
-No crime?

01:07:11.470 --> 01:07:12.353
Zero!

01:07:13.590 --> 01:07:15.014
She moved in here.

01:07:15.081 --> 01:07:16.963
She'll tell you the same d*** thing.

01:07:17.030 --> 01:07:19.542
-Where'd you move in from?
-Amarillo, Texas.

01:07:19.609 --> 01:07:20.492
Oh, no way.

01:07:21.090 --> 01:07:23.323
How do you like it up here
compared to Texas?

01:07:23.390 --> 01:07:24.753
Oh, I love it here.

01:07:25.220 --> 01:07:27.744
I loved Amarillo too,
but my mom and dad

01:07:28.315 --> 01:07:30.164
needed me to take care of them.

01:07:30.231 --> 01:07:32.019
-So I moved up here.
-Oh, okay.

01:07:32.086 --> 01:07:34.201
And you agree, no crime here?

01:07:36.450 --> 01:07:37.606
Very, very little.

01:07:38.180 --> 01:07:42.886
-That's what you want in today's world.
-There's a gun and the keys in the truck.

01:07:43.650 --> 01:07:46.523
-Leave the keys
and the guns in, you're all good.

01:07:46.590 --> 01:07:48.713
Yeah, nobody's gonna bother you.

01:07:48.780 --> 01:07:51.996
You guys self-regulate.
You're not gonna let it get out of line.

01:07:52.063 --> 01:07:53.181
-Well, yeah.
-Right?

01:07:53.814 --> 01:07:55.343
Or you got a good sheriff?

01:07:56.269 --> 01:07:57.798
-Got a good what?
-Sheriff.

01:07:59.675 --> 01:08:01.577
Sorry, my accent's bad.

01:08:01.644 --> 01:08:04.299
Sh*t, we are our own sheriff.

01:08:05.420 --> 01:08:06.863
Is my accent pretty bad?

01:08:06.930 --> 01:08:08.584
-No, it's not.
-I can't hear.

01:08:08.651 --> 01:08:10.996
-I've got ear problems.
-Oh, okay.

01:08:11.063 --> 01:08:13.853
I love the accent here. I think it's cool.

01:08:13.920 --> 01:08:15.745
Searcy  County has its own language.

01:08:15.812 --> 01:08:17.718
-You guys got your own language?
-Yeah.

01:08:17.785 --> 01:08:21.745
It took me six months before I could
even understand anything he said.

01:08:22.365 --> 01:08:24.632
-They said things differently here?
-Mm-hmm.

01:08:24.699 --> 01:08:26.203
How so? Like what?

01:08:26.270 --> 01:08:30.251
Well, like he said
he was going jitterbugging,

01:08:30.811 --> 01:08:33.832
which is some kind of fishing,
catching fish.

01:08:34.300 --> 01:08:36.653
And I thought
they were gonna go dancing.

01:08:37.828 --> 01:08:39.701
Because that's what jitterbugging is.

01:08:39.768 --> 01:08:42.434
So for the jitterbug,
she was all dressed up

01:08:42.501 --> 01:08:44.767
and you disappointed her with fishing.

01:08:44.834 --> 01:08:46.006
-Yeah.
-Yeah. We…

01:08:46.679 --> 01:08:48.418
We was fishing. [laughs]

01:08:48.485 --> 01:08:49.905
Well, thanks for the chair.

01:08:49.972 --> 01:08:51.063
Appreciate it.

01:08:51.130 --> 01:08:53.642
She's as opposite from me

01:08:54.116 --> 01:08:56.331
as you can possibly get.

01:08:56.398 --> 01:08:57.633
Well, she is a woman.

01:08:58.437 --> 01:09:00.023
-Do what?
-Politically.

01:09:00.090 --> 01:09:02.390
-Politically, you guys are different?
-Mm-hmm.

01:09:02.457 --> 01:09:05.320
We're completely different.

01:09:05.837 --> 01:09:07.163
But you get along?

01:09:07.230 --> 01:09:09.278
-Oh, most of the time. Yeah.
-[chuckling]

01:09:09.345 --> 01:09:11.189
-Are you a couple or just friends?

01:09:11.256 --> 01:09:13.253
-Oh, no. We're a couple.
-We're a couple.

01:09:13.320 --> 01:09:16.202
What do you two think about
the country right now?

01:09:16.805 --> 01:09:17.864
It's very divided.

01:09:18.470 --> 01:09:19.796
Online it's just…

01:09:19.863 --> 01:09:22.689
-But if you just talk to people…
-I think if you look at…

01:09:22.756 --> 01:09:25.453
I think if you look at your godd*** phone,

01:09:25.520 --> 01:09:28.159
that you're gonna be mad at somebody.

01:09:28.810 --> 01:09:30.763
That's wisdom bomb right there.

01:09:30.830 --> 01:09:34.448
If you look at your godd*** phone,
you're gonna be mad at somebody.

01:09:34.925 --> 01:09:36.451
-Yeah?
-You are.

01:09:36.518 --> 01:09:37.939
I mean, sh*t…

01:09:38.007 --> 01:09:40.466
That's exactly true.

01:09:40.533 --> 01:09:44.190
If you're on social media scrolling,
the rage is gonna hit you eventually.

01:09:44.257 --> 01:09:46.933
If you didn't have that d*** phone,

01:09:49.059 --> 01:09:50.588
everybody would get along.

01:09:51.240 --> 01:09:53.672
'Cause I walk up here as a stranger.

01:09:53.739 --> 01:09:55.874
I say hi. You say hi. You're friendly.

01:09:55.941 --> 01:09:58.522
You don't care where I'm from,
who I voted for, nothing like that.

01:09:58.589 --> 01:10:00.817
I don't give a sh*t.

01:10:00.884 --> 01:10:01.778
That's Snowball.

01:10:01.845 --> 01:10:05.716
Somebody pulls up there at the store,
hey, come over and have a beer.

01:10:05.783 --> 01:10:07.250
-And that's what most of it is.

01:10:08.490 --> 01:10:09.770
Especially in the Ozarks.

01:10:11.062 --> 01:10:13.308
I've had no problem
talking to anyone here today.

01:10:13.375 --> 01:10:17.430
Well, we've been up to
the Northeast doing rock skipping.

01:10:17.910 --> 01:10:19.913
And people are just as friendly there.

01:10:19.980 --> 01:10:22.043
-Maine.
-Northeast Maine.

01:10:22.110 --> 01:10:23.712
Oh, nice.

01:10:23.779 --> 01:10:25.023
Pennsylvania.

01:10:25.090 --> 01:10:27.049
Yeah, he's a rock skipper.

01:10:27.116 --> 01:10:29.121
You're a professional rock skipper?

01:10:29.188 --> 01:10:30.383
-Yeah.
-Seriously?

01:10:30.450 --> 01:10:32.073
How many skips can you get?

01:10:32.140 --> 01:10:35.980
The most I've ever gotten
in competition is like 35.

01:10:36.830 --> 01:10:38.346
You compete rock skipping?

01:10:38.413 --> 01:10:42.920
But the most I've ever done
is probably I think 50 but…

01:10:43.783 --> 01:10:44.843
I compete.

01:10:44.910 --> 01:10:46.601
-Do you have any trophies?

01:10:46.668 --> 01:10:47.551
-Mm-hmm.
-Yeah.

01:10:48.770 --> 01:10:52.729
Okay.
This is the second place and that was '22.

01:10:54.498 --> 01:10:55.811
-These are cool trophies.

01:10:55.878 --> 01:10:59.930
Okay. So that's like the best type
of skipping stone you want.

01:10:59.997 --> 01:11:01.465
-Just like that, right?
-Yeah.

01:11:01.532 --> 01:11:03.821
That's cool.
Did you meet the world champion?

01:11:03.888 --> 01:11:05.363
Oh yeah. He's our bud.

01:11:06.290 --> 01:11:07.845
What's it like living out here?

01:11:07.912 --> 01:11:10.081
It's just simple life, country living?

01:11:10.552 --> 01:11:13.119
Do your work, hang out with buddies,

01:11:14.743 --> 01:11:16.034
pull back some cold ones.

01:11:16.101 --> 01:11:17.582
Sit around, drink beer.

01:11:17.649 --> 01:11:19.251
Not much going on around here.

01:11:19.318 --> 01:11:20.730
Yeah, there's not. Okay.

01:11:21.330 --> 01:11:23.755
Saturdays, the store is open
and we get tourists.

01:11:23.822 --> 01:11:25.822
-What's it like living here?
-Yeah.

01:11:27.930 --> 01:11:31.658
I can make phone calls
and I can have 10 people here

01:11:33.228 --> 01:11:35.462
to help me in five minutes.

01:11:36.350 --> 01:11:38.500
This'd be a good time for a Jim to show up.

01:11:38.567 --> 01:11:40.906
-You're from where?
-I was born in Vermont.

01:11:41.451 --> 01:11:42.745
I live in Florida now.

01:11:43.494 --> 01:11:45.025
Big town, little town?

01:11:45.092 --> 01:11:46.519
Big compared to Snowball.

01:11:46.586 --> 01:11:47.469
Okay.

01:11:48.346 --> 01:11:50.394
Can you call on anybody to have help?

01:11:50.461 --> 01:11:51.499
10 people, no.

01:11:52.160 --> 01:11:54.918
I've only lived there for four years.

01:11:55.804 --> 01:11:57.451
-Four years?
-Yeah.

01:11:58.010 --> 01:11:59.999
You want to show me the general store?

01:12:00.066 --> 01:12:02.085
-Yeah. I work there.
-Love to see it.

01:12:02.549 --> 01:12:04.283
-We're going to the store.
-What?

01:12:04.350 --> 01:12:06.175
We're going to the store.

01:12:06.667 --> 01:12:07.844
-Oh, you are?
-Yeah.

01:12:08.749 --> 01:12:10.514
-You coming?
-Well I'll go too.

01:12:12.390 --> 01:12:16.178
So Alan's got the oldest house
in Snowball over here.

01:12:16.245 --> 01:12:18.303
-That's what we've heard.
-Okay.

01:12:18.370 --> 01:12:21.265
What about that one down there?
Is anyone living in there?

01:12:21.332 --> 01:12:23.567
No. That's been empty for a long time.

01:12:24.040 --> 01:12:25.805
Lots of raccoons live in there.

01:12:25.872 --> 01:12:27.453
And this is an Airbnb.

01:12:28.540 --> 01:12:29.716
This house for sale?

01:12:30.375 --> 01:12:33.142
Yeah. It's for sale.
But yeah, we rent it out.

01:12:33.209 --> 01:12:35.167
Do you know what they're asking for it?

01:12:35.234 --> 01:12:37.689
-$250,000.
-$250? Really? That much?

01:12:37.756 --> 01:12:38.664
Yeah.

01:12:38.731 --> 01:12:40.051
-Alan took the shortcut.

01:12:42.214 --> 01:12:43.803
Oh, this is awesome.

01:12:43.870 --> 01:12:46.773
This is the grocery store
and the post office.

01:12:46.840 --> 01:12:49.992
-People from Snowball are shopping here?
Or who's shopping here?

01:12:50.059 --> 01:12:52.477
-Well, now it's just like for tourists.

01:12:52.950 --> 01:12:57.607
-You getting some tourists by here?
-T-shirts and hats and souvenirs.

01:12:58.210 --> 01:13:00.568
-You got your old PO boxes.
-Yep.

01:13:01.135 --> 01:13:05.000
-And the Snowball, the name came from
some guy misspelled it, right?

01:13:05.067 --> 01:13:08.133
Right. Yeah, it should be Snow Hall.

01:13:09.115 --> 01:13:12.273
But the H looked like a B,
so they called it Snowball.

01:13:12.340 --> 01:13:14.911
-It's his great-grandfather.
-It's my great-grandpa.

01:13:14.978 --> 01:13:17.286
His name was Snow when they sent

01:13:18.319 --> 01:13:22.491
it out as Snow Hall
when it come back it was Snowball

01:13:22.558 --> 01:13:24.955
'cause I guess
he couldn't write worth a sh*t.

01:13:25.022 --> 01:13:25.905
But…

01:13:25.972 --> 01:13:26.855
[chuckling]

01:13:27.736 --> 01:13:28.619
anyway.

01:13:29.202 --> 01:13:30.571
-What are you gonna do?

01:13:30.638 --> 01:13:34.609
Okay, so people should come here to shop
when they're on their road trips?

01:13:34.676 --> 01:13:36.368
Yeah, it still has all the old…

01:13:36.935 --> 01:13:37.900
-What are those?

01:13:37.967 --> 01:13:39.287
The postal stamps.

01:13:40.043 --> 01:13:41.146
-Oh, no way.

01:13:41.213 --> 01:13:43.283
-That's what they look like?
-Mm-hmm.

01:13:44.090 --> 01:13:45.737
I never knew that was there.

01:13:47.419 --> 01:13:49.448
Oh, nice. That's cool.

01:13:49.515 --> 01:13:50.398
-Insured.

01:13:51.130 --> 01:13:53.601
One of them says Snowball.
Oh, there it is.

01:13:54.283 --> 01:13:55.519
Snowball, Arkansas.

01:13:55.586 --> 01:13:57.493
-Snowball, Arkansas. Nice.

01:13:58.530 --> 01:14:00.103
Six or seven-year-old.

01:14:00.170 --> 01:14:05.083
My mom didn't buy me a candy bar
or a pop or whatever.

01:14:05.150 --> 01:14:06.245
I went outside

01:14:07.578 --> 01:14:09.675
and I slammed the d*** door.

01:14:10.380 --> 01:14:13.570
She went out on the porch
and she called me back.

01:14:14.190 --> 01:14:15.073
-Uh-huh.

01:14:15.720 --> 01:14:19.743
There was probably 20 old men
sitting around that stove right there.

01:14:19.810 --> 01:14:21.986
I thought she was gonna whoop my a**.

01:14:23.710 --> 01:14:26.843
She made me open and close that door

01:14:27.390 --> 01:14:28.780
really easily

01:14:29.767 --> 01:14:31.100
a hundred times.

01:14:31.167 --> 01:14:32.108
[Peter chuckles]

01:14:32.841 --> 01:14:35.699
I never was as embarrassed in my life.

01:14:35.766 --> 01:14:38.196
That's the worst embarrassment
I've ever been in.

01:14:38.263 --> 01:14:40.973
-Open and close a hundred times.
-A hundred times.

01:14:41.040 --> 01:14:44.347
In front of all them old bastards
sitting back there.

01:14:46.184 --> 01:14:48.095
Okay, this guy up here?
Yeah.

01:14:48.162 --> 01:14:50.456
With the big feet, that's Buster Scott.

01:14:50.926 --> 01:14:51.940
-What's his story?

01:14:52.007 --> 01:14:54.617
-He had the biggest feet…
-Biggest feet in the world!

01:14:54.684 --> 01:14:56.484
-In the world.
-Is he from around here?

01:14:56.551 --> 01:14:57.849
Yeah.
What size?

01:14:57.916 --> 01:15:00.482
-He has like 16s or something?
-42s.

01:15:00.549 --> 01:15:01.434
Them are real.

01:15:01.501 --> 01:15:03.519
-What? 42s?
-42s.

01:15:03.586 --> 01:15:04.469
Come on.

01:15:05.230 --> 01:15:07.402
He was with Barnum and Bailey.

01:15:08.570 --> 01:15:11.237
Okay, so he was with the traveling circus.

01:15:11.724 --> 01:15:14.251
He made a ton of money.

01:15:14.776 --> 01:15:16.023
Put Snowball on the map?

01:15:16.537 --> 01:15:17.552
-He did.

01:15:17.619 --> 01:15:19.998
I mean, he's famous.

01:15:20.379 --> 01:15:21.555
-Who's buying these?

01:15:21.998 --> 01:15:22.941
-Hunters.

01:15:23.008 --> 01:15:23.891
-Okay.

01:15:23.958 --> 01:15:24.841
-Deer hunters.

01:15:26.377 --> 01:15:27.260
-Thank you.

01:15:28.129 --> 01:15:29.423
-On me.
-Appreciate it.

01:15:29.850 --> 01:15:30.733
Appreciate it.

01:15:33.898 --> 01:15:36.078
All right, guys. End of the road for today.

01:15:36.145 --> 01:15:39.054
I got to say the Arkansas Ozarks

01:15:39.632 --> 01:15:41.891
far exceeded my expectations.

01:15:41.958 --> 01:15:44.584
What a beautiful part of the country.

01:15:44.651 --> 01:15:45.737
I had no idea.

01:15:46.510 --> 01:15:49.067
And this is part of
a greater Arkansas series.

01:15:49.134 --> 01:15:53.209
If you like this video,
check out my last one on Bentonville

01:15:53.276 --> 01:15:55.741
and the one before on Pine Bluff.

01:15:56.157 --> 01:15:59.158
Such a cool place,
such a cool part of America.

01:15:59.689 --> 01:16:02.105
Thanks for coming along
on that journey guys.

